{"title_page": "Alfred Brauner", "text_new": "{{short description|Austrian-French child psychologist and writer}}\n<nowiki></nowiki>{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = Doctor of Philosophy \n| name               = Alfred Brauner\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1910|7|3|df=y}}<ref name=\"Mouchenik\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Mouchenik  | first1 = Yoram  | authorlink = | title = Les enfants dans la guerre. Entretien avec Alfred Brauner | doi = 10.3917/lautr.031.0010\n | journal = L'Autre, Cliniques, Cultures et Soci\u00e9t\u00e9s | volume = 11  | issue = 1  | pages = 10-17 | year = 2010  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Saint-Mand\u00e9]] [[Val-de-Marne]] [[France]]<ref name=\"Mouchenik\"/>\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2002|12|01|1910|07|03}}<ref name=\"\u00c0 Alfred Brauner \">{{Cite journal | last1 = Perrier | first1 = Edmond | authorlink = Edmond Perrier| title = \u00c0 Alfred Brauner| doi = 10.3917/sn.018.0011 | journal = Sud/ Nord| volume = 18  | issue = 1  | pages = 11-11 | year = 2003 | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>\n| death_place        = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = Austrian \n| citizenship        = French \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = \n| period             = \n| known_for          =  [[child psychology]] ; [[Autism]] ; [[Sociology of childhood]]\n| home_town          = \n| title              = \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| awards             = <!--notable national-level awards only-->\n| website            = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Vienna]] ; [[University of Paris]] <!--will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution-->\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = \n| sub_discipline     = <!--academic discipline specialist area \u2013 e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th-century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist-->\n| workplaces         = <!--full-time positions only, not student positions-->\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Alfred Brauner''' (3 July 1910<ref name=\"Mouchenik\"/> - 1 December 2002<ref name=\"\u00c0 Alfred Brauner \"/>) was an [[Austria|Austrian-born]] [[French people|French]] [[scholar]], [[sociologist]], [[child psychologist]] and [[author]],   who was a volunteer in the [[International Brigades]] during the [[Spanish Civil War]]<ref name=\"\u00d6sterreicher\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.doew.at/erinnern/biographien/spanienarchiv-online/spanienfreiwillige-b/brauner-alfred-dr |title=\u00d6sterreicherInnen f\u00fcr Spaniens Freiheit 1936-1939 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= www.doew.at|publisher=Dokumentationsarchiv des \u00f6sterreichischen Widerstandes}}</ref> and a [[French Resistance|French]] and [[Austrian Resistance]] member during [[Occupied France]].<ref name=\"Resistance\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Brauner  | first1 = Fran\u00e7oise Erna  | authorlink = | title = L'an\u00e9antissement de deux r\u00e9seaux de la r\u00e9sistance | doi = 10.3917/sn.018.0034\n | journal = Sud/Nord | volume = 18  | issue = 1  | pages = 34-48 | year = 2003  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> He has devoted his life to educating refugee, displaced and maladjusted children, participating in the welcoming of Jewish child survivors of the [[Kristallnacht]] and of the [[Nazi concentration camps]] of [[Buchenwald]] and [[Auschwitz]] from 1939 to 1946.<ref name=\"L'accueil\">{{cite book | author = Brauner Alfred, Brauner Fran\u00e7oise| title = L\u2019accueil des enfants survivants| page= | publisher = Cahiers du groupement de recherches pratiques pour l'enfance | year = 1994 | isbn = 978-0-7914-0453-9}}</ref> An early writer on infantile autism,<ref name=\"Living with an autistic child\">{{cite book | author = Brauner Alfred, Brauner Fran\u00e7oise| title = Vivre avec un enfant autistique| page= | publisher = PUF | year = 1978 | isbn = 2-13-037414-X}}</ref> he also pioneered the analysis of children\u2019s drawings in war, creating from 1938 the first collection of drawing-testimonials<ref name=dessin\u00e9>{{cite book | author = Brauner Alfred, Fran\u00e7oise| title = J\u2019ai dessin\u00e9 la guerre. Le dessin de l'enfant dans la guerre | page= | publisher = Elsevier| year = 1991 | isbn = 2-7046-1378-8}}</ref> to offer a unique perspective of the major conflicts of the [[20th century]] through the eyes of children.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Brauner | first1 = Alfred | authorlink = Alfred Brauner| title = Biographie du docteur Fran\u00e7oise Brauner| doi = 10.3917/sn.018.0167| journal = Sud/Nord| volume = 18 | issue = 1 | pages = 167\u201373| year = 2003 | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>\n \n==Background in Austria and education==\n \nBorn on July 3, 1910 in [[Saint-Mand\u00e9]] to [[Austro-Hungarian]] parents spending two years in [[France]] for professional reasons, Alfred Brauner comes from a prestigious Viennese family.<ref name=\" Brauner Claude-Michel\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.enfance-violence-exil.net/fichiers_sgc/BRAUNER.pdf |title=Alfred et Fran\u00e7oise Brauner par leur fils |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website=|publisher=}}</ref> His maternal uncle, Erwin Wexberg, was an Austrian-American neuro-psychiatrist and one of the pioneers of individual psychology.<ref name=\"Erwin Wexberg\">{{cite book | author = Kummel, Ulrich| title = Erwin Wexberg: Ein Leben zwischen Individualpsychologie, Psychoanalyse und Neurologie| page= | publisher = Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-3525401361}}</ref><ref name=\"Brauner Claude-Michel \" />  In Vienna, his family held private classical music concerts at the [[Palais Esterh\u00e1zy]], where [[Sigmund Freud]] was invited.<ref name==\"Cyrulnik >{{cite book | author =Cyrulnik Boris | title = De Chair et d'\u00e2me | page= 229 | publisher = \u00c9ditions Odile Jacob | year = 2006  | isbn = 978-2744197031 }}</ref><ref name=\"Brauner Claude-Michel \" /> In his childhood, he experienced himself the repercussions of the war and witnessed his father leaving for the [[First World War]] to serve in the Austro-Hungarian army.<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/> To save him from the epidemics, during the First World War, his parents sent him to a family in [[Moravia]].<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/> He defended his doctoral thesis in philosophy at the [[University of Vienna]] in 1934, entitled \"''The Unanimism of Jules Romains'',\" a correspondence starting between the young Viennese doctoral student and [[Jules Romains]].<ref name=\"Yannick Ripa\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Ripa | first1 = Yannick | authorlink =| title = Naissance du dessin de guerre. Les \u00e9poux Brauner et les enfants de la guerre civile espagnole | doi = 10.3917/ving.089.0029 | journal = Vingti\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle. Revue d\u2019Histoire| volume = 89 | issue = 1 | pages = 29\u201346| year = 2006 | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> Alfred served in the French army from 1939 and was decorated with the [[Croix de Guerre 1939-1945]], mentioned in dispatches by his division.<ref name=\"\u00c0 Alfred Brauner \"/> In 1946, he defended a thesis at the [[University of Paris]] on \"''The Psychic Repercussions of Modern War on Childhood ''\"<ref name=\"Yannick Ripa\"/> and the same year presented a complementary thesis entitled \"'' Plan, Organization and Results of the Rehabilitation Center for Juvenile Offenders in Kaiserebersdorf near Vienna (Austria) ''\". His younger brother William immigrated to the [[United States]] after [[Kristallnacht]] and died on October 6, 1948 in the [[1948 Georgia USAF Boeing B-29 crash]], which resulted in the US court case [[United States v. Reynolds]]. <ref name=\"LA Times\">{{Cite journal | last1 =Siegel  | first1 =Barry  | authorlink = | title = A Daughter Discovers What Really Happened | doi = | journal = Los Angeles Times | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2004  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref><ref name=\"LA\">{{Cite journal | last1 =Barry  | first1 = Siegel  | authorlink = | title = How the Death of Judy\u2019s Father Made America More Secretive | doi = | journal = Los Angeles Times | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2004  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref><ref name=\"legal affairs\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Freedman  | first1 = Michael  | authorlink = | title = Daughters of the Cold War. Three women sue the Air Force for covering up the deaths of their fathers in a 1948 test flight. | doi = | journal = Legal Affairs | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2004  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n\nAlfred Brauner began his professional activity as an educator in a rehabilitation center for juvenile offenders at Kaiserebersdorf in [[Vienna]] from 1928 to 1933.<ref name=\"Mintec\">{{Cite web|url= https://docplayer.fr/80750089-Fonds-brauner-repertoire-numerique-alfred-et-francoise-brauner.html |title= FONDS BRAUNER:REPERTOIRE NUMERIQUE |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= |publisher=' }}</ref> During the [[Spanish Civil War]], he volunteered in the [[International Brigades]] and was placed at the head of a committee to help evacuees or refugees, because of his previous experience with at-risk youth.<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/><ref name=\"\u00d6sterreicher\"/><ref name=\"Barcelona\">{{Cite web|url=http://sidbrint.ub.edu/en/content/brauner-alfred |title= DADES DEL BRIGADISTA. BRAUNER, Alfred |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= sidbrint.ub.edu/en |publisher=Barcelona University}}</ref><ref name=\"Sugarman\">{{Cite web|url= www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/History/spanjews.pdf|title= Against Fascism - Jews who served in The International Brigade in the Spanish Civil War |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org |publisher=Jewish Military Museum}}</ref> It is a home for children evacuated from Madrid and Asturias after the [[bombing of Guernica]], the goal being to help the Spanish children of Republican territories, in the country and in the combat zone.<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/><ref name=thesis>{{cite book | author =Brauner Alfred | title =The Psychic Repercussions of Modern War on Childhood| page= | publisher =University of Paris La Sorbonne | year = 1946  | isbn = }}</ref> Finally, Alfred returned to France after the defeat of the [[Spanish Republic]].<ref name=\"\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Requeno Gallego | first1 = Manuel   | last2 = Sep\u00falveda Losa     | first2 = Rosa Mar\u00eda | authorlink = | title = La sanidad en las Brigadas Internacionales | doi = | journal = Ediciones de la Universidad de Castilla-La Mancha | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2006  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref><ref name=\"Lefebvre\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Lefebvre  | first1 = Michel  | last2 = Latorre | first2 = Marga | authorlink = | title = Las brigadas internacionales : im\u00e1genes recuperadas | doi = | journal = Lunwerg Editores | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2003  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>\n\nIn 1938, Alfred Brauner and his wife Fritzi discovered the trauma of child victims of war after receiving a set of drawings from a class in Barcelona. These were, in addition to Catalan schoolchildren who were fortunate enough to stay in their school, refugees from Madrid who had witnessed tragic events. The Brauners made a pedo-psychiatric analysis of the child's drawing, a privileged mode of graphic expression of the young child, highlighting what seems to them characteristic of the child's drawing in the war, taking notes, creating medical records and questionnaires. Drawings and writings of children of the Spanish War were the result of a contest organized by Alfred Brauner among the children of Barcelona in 1938 on three themes: \"My life Before the War\", \"What I Saw from the War\" and \"How I See My Life after the War\".<ref name=thesis/> It was then the beginning of their work on \"children who have lived through the war.\" 4000 drawings of refugee children and numerous essays were collected in Spain, which later, along with other drawings of children in war, offered a unique testimony of the conflicts of the 20th century through the eyes of children.<ref name=\"\">{{Cite journal | last1 =Ibarz Serrat  | first1 = Virgilio  | authorlink = | title = Los dibujos infantiles de la guerra 1937-1938: el caso de la ni\u00f1a de Ballobar | doi = | journal = Diario del AltoArag\u00f3n | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2009  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> Their project to publish drawings and testimonies of children in war received the support of [[Ilya Ehrenburg]] and [[Romain Rolland]] who \"regarded this collection as of considerable educational, historical and human interest.\"<ref name=\"Yannick Ripa\"/>\n \nIn 1939, Alfred Brauner welcomed 130 Jewish children from the Palatinate, Berlin and Austria,<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/> survivors of the [[Kristallnacht]] at La Guette, a French castle owned by the Rothschild family and made available by [[Baroness Germaine de Rothschild]].<ref name=\"La Guette\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.ajpn.org/sauvetage-Chateau-de-la-Guette-245.html |title= Ch\u00e2teau de la Guette durant la Seconde Guerre mondiale (WWII) |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= www.ajpn.org/index.php | publisher= }}</ref><ref name=\"\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Lochy  | first1 = Emilie | authorlink = | title = Extrait de l'ouvrage : Enfances en guerre - T\u00e9moignages d'enfants sur la guerre | doi = | journal = Le Cercle Psy | volume = 12  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2014 | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> Alfred\u2019s  intention was to analyze the problems posed in working with children traumatized by their experiences and by separation from their families, with the aim of adapting them to a new life and preparing them for integration into France.<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/> He then described this educational experience in his state thesis, defended in 1946, entitled \"The Psychic Repercussions of Modern War on Childhood.\"<ref name=thesis/>\n \nFrom January 1941, Alfred Brauner entered the [[French Resistance]] and welcomed the [[Austrian resistance]]\u2019s leadership in his [[Rue Bonaparte]] apartment in [[Paris]].<ref name=\"Resistance\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/> With members of the [[\u00d6sterreichische Freiheitsfront]] arriving every morning at a specific time, Alfred Brauner decided to open a German Language course as a cover from [[Gestapo]].<ref name=\"Resistance\"/> In 1945, he helped welcoming and educating 444 surviving boys from the [[Auschwitz]] and [[Buchenwald]] [[concentration camps]], in the scope of the [[Oeuvre de Secours aux Enfants]] (OSE) in [[Ecouis]], [[France]].<ref name=\"Boltanski\">{{cite book | author = Christophe Boltanski | title = La Cache | page= | publisher = Stock | year = 2015  | isbn = 978-2-234-07637-2}}</ref><ref name=\"L'accueil\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/> This welcoming of Buchenwald's child survivors in children's homes inspired the script of the film [[Nina's House]],<ref name=\" \">{{Cite web|url= https://jeudisducinema.be/La-maison-de-Nina |title= La maison de Nina |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= jeudisducinema.be/ | publisher=Les jeudis du cinema }}</ref> as well as the documentary [[The Boys of Buchenwald]].\n \nIn 1950, Alfred Brauner created the \"Practical Research for Children,\" which brings together professionals of childhood in order to develop medico-pedagogical methods intended for the education of children with mental disabilities.<ref name=\"Mintec\"/> In 1955, he founded a day hospital for mentally and physically handicapped children located in the center of Paris, then transferred to Saint-Mand\u00e9, and worked on the rehabilitation of these children, giving priority to their education.<ref name=\"Bio\"/> Alfred Brauner was the ambassador of the association \"''Children Refugees of the World,''\" as well as the only non-physician president of the ''Society of Expression Psychopathology and Art Therapy''.<ref name=\"SFPE\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.sfpe-art-therapie.fr/Quelques-dates-qui-marquent-les-avancees-sur-trois-voies-paralleles_a34.html |title= Quelques dates qui marquent les avanc\u00e9es sur trois voies parall\u00e8les. La voie hexagonale |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= www.sfpe-art-therapie.fr/ | publisher=SFPE}}</ref><ref name=\"BNF\">{{Cite web|url= https://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb118938323 |title= Notice de personne. Brauner, Alfred (1910-2002) |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= catalogue.bnf.fr/index.do | publisher=Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France}}</ref> He was awarded the [[Hans Prinzhorn]] medal of the \"'' German-speaking Society for the Psychopathology of Expression ''\" in 1976.<ref name=\"Prinzhorn\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.dgpa.org/prinzhorn.php?m=6 |title= Preistr\u00e4ger der Hans Prinzhorn Medaille |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= www.dgpa.org/  |publisher=Deutschsprachige Gesellschaft\nf\u00fcr Kunst & Psychopathologie des Ausdrucks e.V.}}</ref> In 1986, [[Jacques Chaban-Delmas]] offered him the medal of the city of [[Bordeaux]].<ref name=\" Brauner Claude-Michel\"/>\n \nOver the course of their career, the Brauners have analyzed children's drawings collected from around the world from children in about 20 countries at war, including the Boer War, the First World War, the Spanish War, Nazi Germany, Poland 1939, concentration camps, Hiroshima-Nagasaki, Polisario, the Israeli-Palestinian Conflict, the Lebanon War, the Algerian War, the Western Sahara War, El Salvador, Afghanistan, the Gulf War, Bosnia, and Chechnya.<ref name=dessin\u00e9/>\n \nFrom 18 January to 10 February 1999, at the [[UNESCO]] headquarters in [[Paris]], an  exhibition was held with more than 200 drawings of children who lived through  war. Entitled \"'' I\u2019ve Drawn the War. A Century of Drawings of Children in Wars (1900-1999) ''\", under the high sponsorship and under the patronage of [[Simone Veil]], these drawings-testimonials belonging to the Brauner collection revealed the impact of the extreme violence of war for the child.<ref name=\"Enfances en guerre\">{{Cite web|url= https://magasindesenfants.hypotheses.org/2215\n |title= Enfances en guerre. T\u00e9moignages d\u2019enfants sur la guerre |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= |publisher=Open Edition}}</ref> This exhibition, which was considered part of the \"World Heritage,\" was then shown in Hiroshima, Jerusalem, Budapest, Vienna and more than 40 cities in Germany.  From 7 to 9 December 2011, a tribute to the 100th anniversary of the birth of the Brauners was organized at UNESCO Headquarters, with the organization of an international colloquium entitled \"'' Childhood in War. Testimonies from Children about War. ''\"<ref name=\"UNESCO \">{{Cite web|url= http://www.unesco.org/new/fr/unesco/events/learning-to-live-together/?tx_browser_pi1%5BshowUid%5D=5278&cHash=54219839bb\n |title= Enfances en guerre. T\u00e9moignages d\u2019enfants sur la guerre |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= fr.unesco.org/ |publisher=}}</ref>  \n\n==Honours and awards==\n* 2002 : ''Premio Margherita Zoebeli'', \u00ab ''La bussola dell\u2019educazione'' \u00bb, Rimini, Italy\n* Ambassador of the association \"''Children Refugees of the World''\"\n* 1986 : Medal of the city of Bordeaux, France \n* 1981 : ''Monza Prize'' for the book \u00ab ''Living with an Autistic Child'' \u00bb, ''Biblioteca Italiana Per Ciechi'' \u00ab ''Regina Margherita'' \u00bb, Villa Reale, Monza, Italy\n* 1979 : ''First Prize'', ''International Rehabilitation Film Festival'' in the category \u00ab ''Mental Health Professional'' \u00bb for the film \u00ab ''Maison sans fen\u00eatres'' \u00bb, New York City, United States. \n* 1976: Hans-Prinzhorn Medal, ''German society of Psychophysiology and its applications'' (DGPA), Munich, Germany \n* 1970 : 3rd Prize, 6th Congress of the International Society of Psychopathology of Expression  (SIPE), Istanbul, Turkey\n* 1970-1973 : President of the ''French Society of psychopathology of expression and Art'' \n* ''Croix de guerre 1939-1945'', mentioned in dispatches by his division\n\n===Major works by Brauner===\n\n\nThe titles of the following publications have been translated from German or French into English and have been put in brackets.\n\n====Thesis====\n* (1946), ''Plan, organisation et r\u00e9sultats de la maison de r\u00e9\u00e9ducation de l'enfance d\u00e9linquante \u00e0 Kaiser-Ebersdorf, pr\u00e8s de Vienne, Autriche'' (Plan, Organization and Results of the Rehabilitation Center for Juvenile Offenders in Kaiserebersdorf near Vienna, Austria) (in French), complementary thesis, University of Paris La Sorbonne. \n* (1946), ''Les r\u00e9percussions psychiques de la guerre moderne sur l'enfance'' (The Psychic Repercussions of Modern War on Childhood) (in French), Higher doctorate (th\u00e8se d\u2019\u00c9tat), University of Paris La Sorbonne. \n* (1934), ''Der Unanimismus Jules Romains'' (The Unanimism of Jules Romains) (in German), Ph.D. thesis, University of Vienna.\n \n====Individual work====\n* (1997), ''Psy, es-tu l\u00e0 ?'' (Pdoc, are you in?) (in French), Groupement de recherches pratiques pour l'enfance, {{ISBN|2-9511382-0-2}}\n* (1976), ''Les Enfants des Confins'' (in French),  Grasset, Paris, {{ISBN|2-246-00359-8}}\n* (1963), ''Titine et l'\u00e9ducation moderne. Une satire.'' (Titine and the Modern Education. A Satire.) (in French), Groupement de recherches pratiques, Saint-Mand\u00e9.\n* (1956), ''Pour en faire des hommes. \u00c9tude sur le jeu et le langage chez les enfants \"inadapt\u00e9s sociaux\"'' (Study on play and language in \u00ab socially maladjusted \u00bb children), S.A.B.R.I., Paris.\n* (1951), ''Nos livres d'enfants ont menti !'' (Our Childhood Books Lied to Us!) (in French),   S.A.B.R.I., Paris (preface by Henri Wallon).\n* (1946), ''Ces enfants ont v\u00e9cu la guerre'' (These Children Have Lived through the War) (in French), \u00c9ditions Sociales Fran\u00e7aises, Paris.\n* (1938) (dir. Alfred Brauner), ''The Spanish Children and the International Brigades'' ; (translation in 5 languages : Les enfants espagnols et les Brigades internationales ; Die spanischen Kinder und die Internationalen Brigaden ; Spanelsk\u00e9 deti a Internacionalni Brig\u00e1dy), Comit\u00e9 Pro-Ni\u00f1os Espa\u00f1oles de las Brigadas Internacionales, Barcelona.\n\n====Collective work====\n* (2001), (with F. Brauner), ''L'expression dramatique chez l'enfant : Pris dans une guerre, handicap\u00e9 mental'' (The dramatic expression in children : Caught in the war, special need) (in French),  Cahiers du groupement de recherches pratiques pour l'enfance, Saint-Mand\u00e9.\n* (1994), (with F. Brauner), ''L'accueil des enfants survivants'', (The Welcoming of the Child Survivors) (in French), Cahiers du groupement de recherches pratiques pour l'enfance, Saint-Mand\u00e9.\n* (1991), (with F. Brauner), ''J'ai dessin\u00e9 la guerre. Le dessin de l'enfant dans la guerre'' (I've drawn the war. Children's Drawings in the War) (in French), \u00c9ditions Scientifiques fran\u00e7aises, Paris, {{ISBN|2-7046-1378-8}}\n* (1986), (with F. Brauner), ''L'Enfant d\u00e9r\u00e9el : histoire des autismes depuis les contes de f\u00e9es. Fictions litt\u00e9raires et r\u00e9alit\u00e9s cliniques'' (History of Autism since the Fairy Tales) (in French), Privat, 1986, Toulouse, {{ISBN|2-7089-7426-2}}\n* (1982), (with F. Brauner), ''Vivre avec un enfant autistique'' (Living with an Autistic Child) (in French), Paris,  PUF, Paris, 2nd Ed., {{ISBN|2-13-037414-X}}\n* (1978), (with F. Brauner), ''L'expression psychotique chez l'enfant'' (The Psychotic Expression in Children) (in French),  PUF, Paris.\n* (1978), (with F. Brauner), ''Vivre avec un enfant autistique'' (Living with an Autistic Child) (in French),  PUF,  {{ISBN|2-13-037414-X}}\nSpanish translation: (1981), ''Vivir con un nino autistico'',  Paidos Iberica Ediciones S A, {{ISBN|978-8475091143}}\n\nItalian translation: (2007), ''Vivere con un bambino autistico'',  Giunti Editore, {{ISBN|978-8809041141}}\n* (1976), (with F. Brauner), ''Dessins d'enfants de la guerre d'Espagne'' (Child Drawings of the Spanish Civil War),  Groupement de Recherches Pratiques pour l'Enfance, Saint Mand\u00e9.\n\n====Academic articles (selection)====\n*       (2003), ''Biographie du docteur Fran\u00e7oise Brauner'' (Biography of Doctor Fran\u00e7oise Brauner) (in French), Sud/Nord, (Vol.18), p.167-173.\n*       (2003), ''L'extermination des Boers, il y a cent ans'' (The Extermination of Boers, a hundred years ago) (in French), Sud/Nord, (Vol.18), p.30-33.\n*\t(2000), (with F. Brauner), ''Des guerres et des enfants handicap\u00e9s mentaux'' (Wars and Special Needs Children) (in French), Revue Europ\u00e9enne du Handicap Mental, p. 29-37.\n*\t(1999), ''Ces enfants ont v\u00e9cu la guerre, Les enfants de La Guette. Souvenirs et documents (1938-1945)'' (These Children Have Lived through the War. La Guette Children. Memories and documents) (1938-1945) (in French), Center of Contemporary Jewish Documentation (CDJC), p. 57.\n*\t(1986), (with F. Brauner), ''Pictures from an exhibition, Children in War: Drawings from the Afghan Refugee Camps'' (in English), (Preface by Sayed B. Majrooh), Central Asian Survey, Incidental Papers Series No 5, London,  Society for Central Asian Studies.\n*\t(1986), (with F. Brauner), ''Children's Drawings and Nuclear War'' (in English), JAMA: The Journal of the American Medical Association 256(5) p.613-616 \n*\t(1985), (with F. Brauner), ''Les enfants d\u00e9port\u00e9s pendant la deuxi\u00e8me guerre mondiale et leurs descendants'' (The Deported Children during the Second World War and their Descendants) (in French), Revue de Neuropsychiatrie de l'enfance et de l'adolescence, No 6, 1985, p. 251-259.\n\n==== Filmography (selection) ====\n* ''Pour en faire des hommes'', Cinemath, Sandoz. \n* ''Trois enfants psychotiques s\u2019expriment'' (Three Psychotic Children speak up), Cinemath, Sandoz, Paris. \n* ''Loin du monde'' (Far from the World) (autism), Cinemath, Sandoz. \n* ''Com\u00e9diens QI +50'' (Actors IQ +50), Cinemath Sandoz et Sp\u00e9cia, Tours : (3rd prize), Istanbul, Turkey, 1970 ; ''Certificate of Merit Award'', ''International Rehabilitation Film Festival'', New York City, 1979.\n* ''Maison sans fen\u00eatre'' (House without Windows), Cinemath, Sandoz et Sp\u00e9cia, 1979 : ''First Prize'', ''International Rehabilitation Film Festival'', New York City, 1979).\n* ''Enfants-masques'' (Children-Masks), Cinemath, Sandoz. \n* ''Inadapt\u00e9s de 15 \u00e0 20'' (Maladjusted from 15 to 20), Groupement de Recherches pratiques pour l'Enfance.\n \n\n=== Bibliography ===\n \n===In English=== \n* (2012), Duroux Rose, Milkovitch-Rioux Catherine, ''I have Drawn Pictures of the War. The Eye of Fran\u00e7oise and Alfred Brauner'', Pu Blaise Pascal.\n\n===In French=== \n* (2013), Duroux Rose, Milkovitch-Rioux Catherine, ''Enfances en guerre. T\u00e9moignages d'enfants sur la guerre'',  L'\u00c9quinoxe.\n* (1996), Pasteur Paul, Kreissler F\u00e9lix, ''Actes du Colloque. Les Autrichiens dans la R\u00e9sistance'' (Conference proceedings. Austrians in the Resistance), Publications de l'Universit\u00e9 de Rouen, Centre d'\u00e9tudes et de recherches autrichiennes, Rouen.\n\n===In German=== \n\n* (2016), Sch\u00fctz Edgar, ''\u00d6sterreichische JournalistInnen und Publizistlnnen im Spanischen B\u00fcrgerkrieg 1936 - 1939'',  LIT Verlag, Vienna.\n* (2003), Landauer Hans, Hackl Erich, ''Lexikon der \u00f6sterreichischen Spanienk\u00e4mpfer: 1936-1939'', Verlag der Theodor-Kramer-Ges., Vienna, {{ISBN|3901602186}}.\n \n===Articles===\n* (2013), Poblaci\u00f3n F\u00e9lix, ''Los Brauner y los dibujos de los ni\u00f1os de las guerras'' (in Spanish), Cr\u00f3nica Popular. \n* (2010), Mouchenik Yoram, ''Les enfants dans la guerre. Entretien avec Alfred BRAUNER'', L'Autre, (Vol. 11), p. 10-17 (in French). \n* (2006), Ripa Yannick, ''Naissance du dessin de guerre. Les \u00e9poux Brauner et les enfants de la guerre civile espagnole'', dans Vingti\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle : Revue d'histoire, (No 89), p. 29-46 (in French). \n* (2004), Guillermo Casa\u00f1, ''Benic\u00e0ssim, hospital de las Brigadas Internacionales'' (Etapas Dumont y Ritterman), Aula militar, (in Spanish).\n* (2003), Perrier Edmond, ''\u00c0 Alfred Brauner'', Sud/Nord, (No 18), p. 11-11 (in French). \n* (1947), Mauco Georges, ''Brauner Alfred. - Ces enfants ont v\u00e9cu la guerre'', Population,  (Vol. 2), p. 383-384 (in French).\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Childhood in War]]\n* [[\u00d6sterreichische Freiheitsfront]]\n* [[International Brigades]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brauner, Alfred}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Child psychologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:French people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Vienna alumni]]\n[[Category:Autism researchers]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n[[Category:French people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:Foreign volunteers in the Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:French Resistance members]]\n[[Category:Austrian Resistance members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Austrian-French child psychologist and writer}}\n<nowiki></nowiki>{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = Doctor of Philosophy \n| name               = Alfred Brauner\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1910|7|3|df=y}}<ref name=\"Mouchenik\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Mouchenik  | first1 = Yoram  | authorlink = | title = Les enfants dans la guerre. Entretien avec Alfred Brauner | doi = 10.3917/lautr.031.0010\n | journal = L'Autre, Cliniques, Cultures et Soci\u00e9t\u00e9s | volume = 11  | issue = 1  | pages = 10-17 | year = 2010  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Saint-Mand\u00e9]] [[Val-de-Marne]] [[France]]<ref name=\"Mouchenik\"/>\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2002|12|01|1910|07|03}}<ref name=\"\u00c0 Alfred Brauner \">{{Cite journal | last1 = Perrier | first1 = Edmond | authorlink = Edmond Perrier| title = \u00c0 Alfred Brauner| doi = 10.3917/sn.018.0011 | journal = Sud/ Nord| volume = 18  | issue = 1  | pages = 11-11 | year = 2003 | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>\n| death_place        = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = Austrian \n| citizenship        = French \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = \n| period             = \n| known_for          =  [[child psychology]] ; [[Autism]] ; [[Sociology of childhood]]\n| home_town          = \n| title              = \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| awards             = <!--notable national-level awards only-->\n| website            = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Vienna]] ; [[University of Paris]] <!--will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution-->\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = \n| sub_discipline     = <!--academic discipline specialist area \u2013 e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th-century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist-->\n| workplaces         = <!--full-time positions only, not student positions-->\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Alfred Brauner''' (3 July 1910<ref name=\"Mouchenik\"/> - 1 December 2002<ref name=\"\u00c0 Alfred Brauner \"/>) was an [[Austria|Austrian-born]] [[French people|French]] [[scholar]], [[sociologist]], [[child psychologist]] and [[author]],   who was a volunteer in the [[International Brigades]] during the [[Spanish Civil War]]<ref name=\"\u00d6sterreicher\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.doew.at/erinnern/biographien/spanienarchiv-online/spanienfreiwillige-b/brauner-alfred-dr |title=\u00d6sterreicherInnen f\u00fcr Spaniens Freiheit 1936-1939 |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= www.doew.at|publisher=Dokumentationsarchiv des \u00f6sterreichischen Widerstandes}}</ref> and a [[French Resistance|French]] and [[Austrian Resistance]] member during [[Occupied France]].<ref name=\"Resistance\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Brauner  | first1 = Fran\u00e7oise Erna  | authorlink = | title = L'an\u00e9antissement de deux r\u00e9seaux de la r\u00e9sistance | doi = 10.3917/sn.018.0034\n | journal = Sud/Nord | volume = 18  | issue = 1  | pages = 34-48 | year = 2003  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> He has devoted his life to educating refugee, displaced and maladjusted children, participating in the welcoming of Jewish child survivors of the [[Kristallnacht]] and of the [[Nazi concentration camps]] of [[Buchenwald]] and [[Auschwitz]] from 1939 to 1946.<ref name=\"L'accueil\">{{cite book | author = Brauner Alfred, Brauner Fran\u00e7oise| title = L\u2019accueil des enfants survivants| page= | publisher = Cahiers du groupement de recherches pratiques pour l'enfance | year = 1994 | isbn = 978-0-7914-0453-9}}</ref> An early writer on infantile autism,<ref name=\"Living with an autistic child\">{{cite book | author = Brauner Alfred, Brauner Fran\u00e7oise| title = Vivre avec un enfant autistique| page= | publisher = PUF | year = 1978 | isbn = 2-13-037414-X}}</ref> he also pioneered the analysis of children\u2019s drawings in war, creating from 1938 the first collection of drawing-testimonials<ref name=dessin\u00e9>{{cite book | author = Brauner Alfred, Fran\u00e7oise| title = J\u2019ai dessin\u00e9 la guerre. Le dessin de l'enfant dans la guerre | page= | publisher = Elsevier| year = 1991 | isbn = 2-7046-1378-8}}</ref> to offer a unique perspective of the major conflicts of the [[20th century]] through the eyes of children.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Brauner | first1 = Alfred | authorlink = Alfred Brauner| title = Biographie du docteur Fran\u00e7oise Brauner| doi = 10.3917/sn.018.0167| journal = Sud/Nord| volume = 18 | issue = 1 | pages = 167\u201373| year = 2003 | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>\n \n==Background in Austria and education==\n \nBorn on July 3, 1910 in [[Saint-Mand\u00e9]] to [[Austro-Hungarian]] parents spending two years in [[France]] for professional reasons, Alfred Brauner comes from a prestigious Viennese family.<ref name=\" Brauner Claude-Michel\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.enfance-violence-exil.net/fichiers_sgc/BRAUNER.pdf |title=Alfred et Fran\u00e7oise Brauner par leur fils |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website=|publisher=}}</ref> His maternal uncle, Erwin Wexberg, was an Austrian-American neuro-psychiatrist and one of the pioneers of individual psychology.<ref name=\"Erwin Wexberg\">{{cite book | author = Kummel, Ulrich| title = Erwin Wexberg: Ein Leben zwischen Individualpsychologie, Psychoanalyse und Neurologie| page= | publisher = Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-3525401361}}</ref><ref name=\"Brauner Claude-Michel \" />  In Vienna, his family held private classical music concerts at the [[Palais Esterh\u00e1zy]], where [[Sigmund Freud]] was invited.<ref name==\"Cyrulnik >{{cite book | author =Cyrulnik Boris | title = De Chair et d'\u00e2me | page= 229 | publisher = \u00c9ditions Odile Jacob | year = 2006  | isbn = 978-2744197031 }}</ref><ref name=\"Brauner Claude-Michel \" /> In his childhood, he experienced himself the repercussions of the war and witnessed his father leaving for the [[First World War]] to serve in the Austro-Hungarian army.<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/> To save him from the epidemics, during the First World War, his parents sent him to a family in [[Moravia]].<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/> He defended his doctoral thesis in philosophy at the [[University of Vienna]] in 1934, entitled \"''The Unanimism of Jules Romains'',\" a correspondence starting between the young Viennese doctoral student and [[Jules Romains]].<ref name=\"Yannick Ripa\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Ripa | first1 = Yannick | authorlink =| title = Naissance du dessin de guerre. Les \u00e9poux Brauner et les enfants de la guerre civile espagnole | doi = 10.3917/ving.089.0029 | journal = Vingti\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle. Revue d\u2019Histoire| volume = 89 | issue = 1 | pages = 29\u201346| year = 2006 | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> Alfred served in the French army from 1939 and was decorated with the [[Croix de Guerre 1939-1945]], mentioned in dispatches by his division.<ref name=\"\u00c0 Alfred Brauner \"/> In 1946, he defended a thesis at the [[University of Paris]] on \"''The Psychic Repercussions of Modern War on Childhood ''\"<ref name=\"Yannick Ripa\"/> and the same year presented a complementary thesis entitled \"'' Plan, Organization and Results of the Rehabilitation Center for Juvenile Offenders in Kaiserebersdorf near Vienna (Austria) ''\". His younger brother William immigrated to the [[United States]] after [[Kristallnacht]] and died on October 6, 1948 in the [[1948 Georgia USAF Boeing B-29 crash]], which resulted in the US court case [[United States v. Reynolds]]. <ref name=\"LA Times\">{{Cite journal | last1 =Siegel  | first1 =Barry  | authorlink = | title = A Daughter Discovers What Really Happened | doi = | journal = Los Angeles Times | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2004  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref><ref name=\"LA\">{{Cite journal | last1 =Barry  | first1 = Siegel  | authorlink = | title = How the Death of Judy\u2019s Father Made America More Secretive | doi = | journal = Los Angeles Times | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2004  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref><ref name=\"legal affairs\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Freedman  | first1 = Michael  | authorlink = | title = Daughters of the Cold War. Three women sue the Air Force for covering up the deaths of their fathers in a 1948 test flight. | doi = | journal = Legal Affairs | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2004  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n\nAlfred Brauner began his professional activity as an educator in a rehabilitation center for juvenile offenders at Kaiserebersdorf in [[Vienna]] from 1928 to 1933.<ref name=\"Mintec\">{{Cite web|url= https://docplayer.fr/80750089-Fonds-brauner-repertoire-numerique-alfred-et-francoise-brauner.html |title= FONDS BRAUNER:REPERTOIRE NUMERIQUE |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= |publisher=' }}</ref> During the [[Spanish Civil War]], he volunteered in the [[International Brigades]] and was placed at the head of a committee to help evacuees or refugees, because of his previous experience with at-risk youth.<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/><ref name=\"\u00d6sterreicher\"/><ref name=\"Barcelona\">{{Cite web|url=http://sidbrint.ub.edu/en/content/brauner-alfred |title= DADES DEL BRIGADISTA. BRAUNER, Alfred |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= sidbrint.ub.edu/en |publisher=Barcelona University}}</ref><ref name=\"Sugarman\">{{Cite web|url= www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/History/spanjews.pdf|title= Against Fascism - Jews who served in The International Brigade in the Spanish Civil War |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org |publisher=Jewish Military Museum}}</ref> It is a home for children evacuated from Madrid and Asturias after the [[bombing of Guernica]], the goal being to help the Spanish children of Republican territories, in the country and in the combat zone.<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/><ref name=thesis>{{cite book | author =Brauner Alfred | title =The Psychic Repercussions of Modern War on Childhood| page= | publisher =University of Paris La Sorbonne | year = 1946  | isbn = }}</ref> Finally, Alfred returned to France after the defeat of the [[Spanish Republic]].<ref name=\"\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Requeno Gallego | first1 = Manuel   | last2 = Sep\u00falveda Losa     | first2 = Rosa Mar\u00eda | authorlink = | title = La sanidad en las Brigadas Internacionales | doi = | journal = Ediciones de la Universidad de Castilla-La Mancha | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2006  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref><ref name=\"Lefebvre\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Lefebvre  | first1 = Michel  | last2 = Latorre | first2 = Marga | authorlink = | title = Las brigadas internacionales : im\u00e1genes recuperadas | doi = | journal = Lunwerg Editores | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2003  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>\n\nIn 1938, Alfred Brauner and his wife Fritzi discovered the trauma of child victims of war after receiving a set of drawings from a class in Barcelona. These were, in addition to Catalan schoolchildren who were fortunate enough to stay in their school, refugees from Madrid who had witnessed tragic events. The Brauners made a pedo-psychiatric analysis of the child's drawing, a privileged mode of graphic expression of the young child, highlighting what seems to them characteristic of the child's drawing in the war, taking notes, creating medical records and questionnaires. Drawings and writings of children of the Spanish War were the result of a contest organized by Alfred Brauner among the children of Barcelona in 1938 on three themes: \"My life Before the War\", \"What I Saw from the War\" and \"How I See My Life after the War\".<ref name=thesis/> It was then the beginning of their work on \"children who have lived through the war.\" 4000 drawings of refugee children and numerous essays were collected in Spain, which later, along with other drawings of children in war, offered a unique testimony of the conflicts of the 20th century through the eyes of children.<ref name=\"\">{{Cite journal | last1 =Ibarz Serrat  | first1 = Virgilio  | authorlink = | title = Los dibujos infantiles de la guerra 1937-1938: el caso de la ni\u00f1a de Ballobar | doi = | journal = Diario del AltoArag\u00f3n | volume =  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2009  | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> Their project to publish drawings and testimonies of children in war received the support of [[Ilya Ehrenburg]] and [[Romain Rolland]] who \"regarded this collection as of considerable educational, historical and human interest.\"<ref name=\"Yannick Ripa\"/>\n \nIn 1939, Alfred Brauner welcomed 130 Jewish children from the Palatinate, Berlin and Austria,<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/> survivors of the [[Kristallnacht]] at La Guette, a French castle owned by the Rothschild family and made available by [[Baroness Germaine de Rothschild]].<ref name=\"La Guette\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.ajpn.org/sauvetage-Chateau-de-la-Guette-245.html |title= Ch\u00e2teau de la Guette durant la Seconde Guerre mondiale (WWII) |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= www.ajpn.org/index.php | publisher= }}</ref><ref name=\"\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Lochy  | first1 = Emilie | authorlink = | title = Extrait de l'ouvrage : Enfances en guerre - T\u00e9moignages d'enfants sur la guerre | doi = | journal = Le Cercle Psy | volume = 12  | issue =  | pages = | year = 2014 | jstor =| pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> Alfred\u2019s  intention was to analyze the problems posed in working with children traumatized by their experiences and by separation from their families, with the aim of adapting them to a new life and preparing them for integration into France.<ref name=\"L'accueil\"/> He then described this educational experience in his state thesis, defended in 1946, entitled \"The Psychic Repercussions of Modern War on Childhood.\"<ref name=thesis/>\n \nFrom January 1941, Alfred Brauner entered the [[French Resistance]] and welcomed the [[Austrian resistance]]\u2019s leadership in his [[Rue Bonaparte]] apartment in [[Paris]].<ref name=\"Resistance\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/> With members of the [[\u00d6sterreichische Freiheitsfront]] arriving every morning at a specific time, Alfred Brauner decided to open a German Language course as a cover from [[Gestapo]].<ref name=\"Resistance\"/> In 1945, he helped welcoming and educating 444 surviving boys from the [[Auschwitz]] and [[Buchenwald]] [[concentration camps]], in the scope of the [[Oeuvre de Secours aux Enfants]] (OSE) in [[Ecouis]], [[France]].<ref name=\"Boltanski\">{{cite book | author = Christophe Boltanski | title = La Cache | page= | publisher = Stock | year = 2015  | isbn = 978-2-234-07637-2}}</ref><ref name=\"L'accueil\"/><ref name=\"Bio\"/> This welcoming of Buchenwald's child survivors in children's homes inspired the script of the film [[Nina's House]],<ref name=\" \">{{Cite web|url= https://jeudisducinema.be/La-maison-de-Nina |title= La maison de Nina |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= jeudisducinema.be/ | publisher=Les jeudis du cinema }}</ref> as well as the documentary [[The Boys of Buchenwald]].\n \nIn 1950, Alfred Brauner created the \"Practical Research for Children,\" which brings together professionals of childhood in order to develop medico-pedagogical methods intended for the education of children with mental disabilities.<ref name=\"Mintec\"/> In 1955, he founded a day hospital for mentally and physically handicapped children located in the center of Paris, then transferred to Saint-Mand\u00e9, and worked on the rehabilitation of these children, giving priority to their education.<ref name=\"Bio\"/> Alfred Brauner was the ambassador of the association \"''Children Refugees of the World,''\" as well as the only non-physician president of the ''Society of Expression Psychopathology and Art Therapy''.<ref name=\"SFPE\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.sfpe-art-therapie.fr/Quelques-dates-qui-marquent-les-avancees-sur-trois-voies-paralleles_a34.html |title= Quelques dates qui marquent les avanc\u00e9es sur trois voies parall\u00e8les. La voie hexagonale |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= www.sfpe-art-therapie.fr/ | publisher=SFPE}}</ref><ref name=\"BNF\">{{Cite web|url= https://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb118938323 |title= Notice de personne. Brauner, Alfred (1910-2002) |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= catalogue.bnf.fr/index.do | publisher=Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France}}</ref> He was awarded the [[Hans Prinzhorn]] medal of the \"'' German-speaking Society for the Psychopathology of Expression ''\" in 1976.<ref name=\"Prinzhorn\">{{Cite web|url= https://www.dgpa.org/prinzhorn.php?m=6 |title= Preistr\u00e4ger der Hans Prinzhorn Medaille |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= www.dgpa.org/  |publisher=Deutschsprachige Gesellschaft\nf\u00fcr Kunst & Psychopathologie des Ausdrucks e.V.}}</ref> In 1986, [[Jacques Chaban-Delmas]] offered him the medal of the city of [[Bordeaux]].<ref name=\" Brauner Claude-Michel\"/>\n \nOver the course of their career, the Brauners have analyzed children's drawings collected from around the world from children in about 20 countries at war, including the Boer War, the First World War, the Spanish War, Nazi Germany, Poland 1939, concentration camps, Hiroshima-Nagasaki, Polisario, the Israeli-Palestinian Conflict, the Lebanon War, the Algerian War, the Western Sahara War, El Salvador, Afghanistan, the Gulf War, Bosnia, and Chechnya.<ref name=dessin\u00e9/>\n \nFrom 18 January to 10 February 1999, at the [[UNESCO]] headquarters in [[Paris]], an  exhibition was held with more than 200 drawings of children who lived through  war. Entitled \"'' I\u2019ve Drawn the War. A Century of Drawings of Children in Wars (1900-1999) ''\", under the high sponsorship and under the patronage of [[Simone Veil]], these drawings-testimonials belonging to the Brauner collection revealed the impact of the extreme violence of war for the child.<ref name=\"Enfances en guerre\">{{Cite web|url= https://magasindesenfants.hypotheses.org/2215\n |title= Enfances en guerre. T\u00e9moignages d\u2019enfants sur la guerre |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= |publisher=Open Edition}}</ref> This exhibition, which was considered part of the \"World Heritage,\" was then shown in Hiroshima, Jerusalem, Budapest, Vienna and more than 40 cities in Germany.  From 7 to 9 December 2011, a tribute to the 100th anniversary of the birth of the Brauners was organized at UNESCO Headquarters, with the organization of an international colloquium entitled \"'' Childhood in War. Testimonies from Children about War. ''\"<ref name=\"UNESCO \">{{Cite web|url= http://www.unesco.org/new/fr/unesco/events/learning-to-live-together/?tx_browser_pi1%5BshowUid%5D=5278&cHash=54219839bb\n |title= Enfances en guerre. T\u00e9moignages d\u2019enfants sur la guerre |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website= fr.unesco.org/ |publisher=}}</ref>  \n\n==Honours and awards==\n* 2002 : ''Premio Margherita Zoebeli'', \u00ab ''La bussola dell\u2019educazione'' \u00bb, Rimini, Italy\n* Ambassador of the association \"''Children Refugees of the World''\"\n* 1986 : Medal of the city of Bordeaux, France \n* 1981 : ''Monza Prize'' for the book \u00ab ''Living with an Autistic Child'' \u00bb, ''Biblioteca Italiana Per Ciechi'' \u00ab ''Regina Margherita'' \u00bb, Villa Reale, Monza, Italy\n* 1979 : ''First Prize'', ''International Rehabilitation Film Festival'' in the category \u00ab ''Mental Health Professional'' \u00bb for the film \u00ab ''Maison sans fen\u00eatres'' \u00bb, New York City, United States. \n* 1976: Hans-Prinzhorn Medal, ''German society of Psychophysiology and its applications'' (DGPA), Munich, Germany \n* 1970 : 3rd Prize, 6th Congress of the International Society of Psychopathology of Expression  (SIPE), Istanbul, Turkey\n* 1970-1973 : President of the ''French Society of psychopathology of expression and Art'' \n* ''Croix de guerre 1939-1945'', mentioned in dispatches by his division\n\n===Major works by Brauner===\n\n\nThe titles of the following publications have been translated from German or French into English and have been put in brackets.\n\n====Thesis====\n* (1946), ''Plan, organisation et r\u00e9sultats de la maison de r\u00e9\u00e9ducation de l'enfance d\u00e9linquante \u00e0 Kaiser-Ebersdorf, pr\u00e8s de Vienne, Autriche'' (Plan, Organization and Results of the Rehabilitation Center for Juvenile Offenders in Kaiserebersdorf near Vienna, Austria) (in French), complementary thesis, University of Paris La Sorbonne. \n* (1946), ''Les r\u00e9percussions psychiques de la guerre moderne sur l'enfance'' (The Psychic Repercussions of Modern War on Childhood) (in French), Higher doctorate (th\u00e8se d\u2019\u00c9tat), University of Paris La Sorbonne. \n* (1934), ''Der Unanimismus Jules Romains'' (The Unanimism of Jules Romains) (in German), Ph.D. thesis, University of Vienna.\n \n====Individual work====\n* (1997), ''Psy, es-tu l\u00e0 ?'' (Pdoc, are you in?) (in French), Groupement de recherches pratiques pour l'enfance, {{ISBN|2-9511382-0-2}}\n* (1976), ''Les Enfants des Confins'' (in French),  Grasset, Paris, {{ISBN|2-246-00359-8}}\n* (1963), ''Titine et l'\u00e9ducation moderne. Une satire.'' (Titine and the modern education. A satire.) (in French), Groupement de recherches pratiques, Saint-Mand\u00e9.\n* (1956), ''Pour en faire des hommes. \u00c9tude sur le jeu et le langage chez les enfants \"inadapt\u00e9s sociaux\"'' (Study on play and language in \u00ab socially maladjusted \u00bb children), S.A.B.R.I., Paris.\n* (1951), ''Nos livres d'enfants ont menti !'' (Our childhood books lied to us!) (in French),   S.A.B.R.I., Paris (preface by Henri Wallon).\n* (1946), ''Ces enfants ont v\u00e9cu la guerre'' (These Children Have Lived through the War) (in French), \u00c9ditions Sociales Fran\u00e7aises, Paris.\n* (1938) (dir. Alfred Brauner), ''The Spanish children and the International Brigades'' ; (translation in 5 languages : Les enfants espagnols et les Brigades internationales ; Die spanischen Kinder und die Internationalen Brigaden ; Spanelsk\u00e9 deti a Internacionalni Brig\u00e1dy), Comit\u00e9 Pro-Ni\u00f1os Espa\u00f1oles de las Brigadas Internacionales, Barcelona.\n\n====Collective work====\n* (2001), (with F. Brauner), ''L'expression dramatique chez l'enfant : Pris dans une guerre, handicap\u00e9 mental'' (The dramatic expression in children : Caught in the war, special need) (in French),  Cahiers du groupement de recherches pratiques pour l'enfance, Saint-Mand\u00e9.\n* (1994), (with F. Brauner), ''L'accueil des enfants survivants'', (The Welcoming of the Child Survivors) (in French), Cahiers du groupement de recherches pratiques pour l'enfance, Saint-Mand\u00e9.\n* (1991), (with F. Brauner), ''J'ai dessin\u00e9 la guerre. Le dessin de l'enfant dans la guerre'' (I've drawn the war. Children's Drawings in the War) (in French), \u00c9ditions Scientifiques fran\u00e7aises, Paris, {{ISBN|2-7046-1378-8}}\n* (1986), (with F. Brauner), ''L'Enfant d\u00e9r\u00e9el : histoire des autismes depuis les contes de f\u00e9es. Fictions litt\u00e9raires et r\u00e9alit\u00e9s cliniques'' (History of Autism since the Fairy Tales) (in French), Privat, 1986, Toulouse, {{ISBN|2-7089-7426-2}}\n* (1982), (with F. Brauner), ''Vivre avec un enfant autistique'' (Living with an Autistic child) (in French), Paris,  PUF, Paris, 2nd Ed., {{ISBN|2-13-037414-X}}\n* (1978), (with F. Brauner), ''L'expression psychotique chez l'enfant'' (The psychotic expression in children) (in French),  PUF, Paris.\n* (1978), (with F. Brauner), ''Vivre avec un enfant autistique'' (Living with an autistic child) (in French),  PUF,  {{ISBN|2-13-037414-X}}\nSpanish translation: (1981), ''Vivir con un nino autistico'',  Paidos Iberica Ediciones S A, {{ISBN|978-8475091143}}\n\nItalian translation: (2007), ''Vivere con un bambino autistico'',  Giunti Editore, {{ISBN|978-8809041141}}\n* (1976), (with F. Brauner), ''Dessins d'enfants de la guerre d'Espagne'' (Child drawings of the Spanish Civil War),  Groupement de Recherches Pratiques pour l'Enfance, Saint Mand\u00e9.\n\n====Academic articles (selection)====\n*       (2003), ''Biographie du docteur Fran\u00e7oise Brauner'' (Biography of doctor Fran\u00e7oise Brauner) (in French), Sud/Nord, (Vol.18), p.167-173.\n*       (2003), ''L'extermination des Boers, il y a cent ans'' (The extermination of Boers, a hundred years ago) (in French), Sud/Nord, (Vol.18), p.30-33.\n*\t(2000), (with F. Brauner), ''Des guerres et des enfants handicap\u00e9s mentaux'' (Wars and Special Needs Children) (in French), Revue Europ\u00e9enne du Handicap Mental, p. 29-37.\n*\t(1999), ''Ces enfants ont v\u00e9cu la guerre, Les enfants de La Guette. Souvenirs et documents (1938-1945)'' (These children have lived through the war. La Guette children. Memories and documents) (1938-1945) (in French), Center of Contemporary Jewish Documentation (CDJC), p. 57.\n*\t(1986), (with F. Brauner), ''Pictures from an exhibition, Children in War: Drawings from the Afghan Refugee Camps'' (in English), (Preface by Sayed B. Majrooh), Central Asian Survey, Incidental Papers Series No 5, London,  Society for Central Asian Studies.\n*\t(1986), (with F. Brauner), ''Children's Drawings and Nuclear War'' (in English), JAMA: The Journal of the American Medical Association 256(5) p.613-616 \n*\t(1985), (with F. Brauner), ''Les enfants d\u00e9port\u00e9s pendant la deuxi\u00e8me guerre mondiale et leurs descendants'' (The deported children during the Second World War and their descendants) (in French), Revue de Neuropsychiatrie de l'enfance et de l'adolescence, No 6, 1985, p. 251-259.\n\n==== Filmography (selection) ====\n* ''Pour en faire des hommes'', Cinemath, Sandoz. \n* ''Trois enfants psychotiques s\u2019expriment'' (Three psychotic children speak up), Cinemath, Sandoz, Paris. \n* ''Loin du monde'' (Far from the World) (autism), Cinemath, Sandoz. \n* ''Com\u00e9diens QI +50'' (Actors IQ +50), Cinemath Sandoz et Sp\u00e9cia, Tours : (3rd prize), Istanbul, Turkey, 1970 ; ''Certificate of Merit Award'', ''International Rehabilitation Film Festival'', New York City, 1979.\n* ''Maison sans fen\u00eatre'' (House without windows), Cinemath, Sandoz et Sp\u00e9cia, 1979 : ''First Prize'', ''International Rehabilitation Film Festival'', New York City, 1979).\n* ''Enfants-masques'' (Children-Masks), Cinemath, Sandoz. \n* ''Inadapt\u00e9s de 15 \u00e0 20'' (Maladjusted from 15 to 20), Groupement de Recherches pratiques pour l'Enfance.\n \n\n=== Bibliography ===\n \n===In English=== \n* (2012), Duroux Rose, Milkovitch-Rioux Catherine, ''I have Drawn Pictures of the War. The Eye of Fran\u00e7oise and Alfred Brauner'', Pu Blaise Pascal.\n\n===In French=== \n* (2013), Duroux Rose, Milkovitch-Rioux Catherine, ''Enfances en guerre. T\u00e9moignages d'enfants sur la guerre'',  L'\u00c9quinoxe.\n* (1996), Pasteur Paul, Kreissler F\u00e9lix, ''Actes du Colloque. Les Autrichiens dans la R\u00e9sistance'' (Austrians in the Resistance, Publications de l'Universit\u00e9 de Rouen, Centre d'\u00e9tudes et de recherches autrichiennes, Rouen.\n\n===In German=== \n\n* (2016), Sch\u00fctz Edgar, ''\u00d6sterreichische JournalistInnen und Publizistlnnen im Spanischen B\u00fcrgerkrieg 1936 - 1939'',  LIT Verlag, Vienna.\n* (2003), Landauer Hans, Hackl Erich, ''Lexikon der \u00f6sterreichischen Spanienk\u00e4mpfer: 1936-1939'', Verlag der Theodor-Kramer-Ges., Vienna, {{ISBN|3901602186}}.\n \n===Articles===\n* (2013), Poblaci\u00f3n F\u00e9lix, ''Los Brauner y los dibujos de los ni\u00f1os de las guerras'' (in Spanish), Cr\u00f3nica Popular. \n* (2010), Mouchenik Yoram, ''Les enfants dans la guerre. Entretien avec Alfred BRAUNER'', L'Autre, (Vol. 11), p. 10-17 (in French). \n* (2006), Ripa Yannick, ''Naissance du dessin de guerre. Les \u00e9poux Brauner et les enfants de la guerre civile espagnole'', dans Vingti\u00e8me Si\u00e8cle : Revue d'histoire, (No 89), p. 29-46 (in French). \n* (2004), Guillermo Casa\u00f1, ''Benic\u00e0ssim, hospital de las Brigadas Internacionales'' (Etapas Dumont y Ritterman), Aula militar, (in Spanish).\n* (2003), Perrier Edmond, ''\u00c0 Alfred Brauner'', Sud/Nord, (No 18), p. 11-11 (in French). \n* (1947), Mauco Georges, ''Brauner Alfred. - Ces enfants ont v\u00e9cu la guerre'', Population,  (Vol. 2), p. 383-384 (in French).\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Childhood in War]]\n* [[\u00d6sterreichische Freiheitsfront]]\n* [[International Brigades]]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brauner, Alfred}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Child psychologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:French people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Vienna alumni]]\n[[Category:Autism researchers]]\n[[Category:People from Vienna]]\n[[Category:French people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:Foreign volunteers in the Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:French Resistance members]]\n[[Category:Austrian Resistance members]]\n", "name_user": "BerlinFR2503", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Brauner"}
{"title_page": "Mark D'Onofrio", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Mark D'Onofrio\n| image = Mark D'Onofrio 2012.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = D'Onofrio with the Miami Hurricanes\n| current_record = \n| contract = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1969|03|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Hoboken, New Jersey]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1988\u20131991\n| player_team1 = [[Penn State Nittany Lions football|Penn State]]\n| player_years2 = 1992\n| player_team2 = [[Green Bay Packers]]\n| player_positions = [[Linebacker]]\n| coach_years1 = 1999\n| coach_team1 = [[Saint Peter's Peacocks football|Saint Peter's]] (LB)\n| coach_years2 = 2000\n| coach_team2 = [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] (DA)\n| coach_years3 = 2001\n| coach_team3 = [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]] (LB)\n| coach_years4 = 2002\u20132003\n| coach_team4 = Rutgers (LB/RC)\n| coach_years5 = 2004\n| coach_team5 = [[Virginia Cavaliers football|Virginia]] (TE/ST)\n| coach_years6 = 2005\n| coach_team6 = Virginia (ILB/ST)\n| coach_years7 = 2006\u20132007\n| coach_team7 = [[Temple Owls football|Temple]] (DC)\n| coach_years8 = 2008\u20132009\n| coach_team8 = Temple (AHC/DC)\n| coach_years9 = 2010\n| coach_team9 = Temple (AHC/DC/LB)\n| coach_years10 = 2011\u20132015\n| coach_team10 = [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami (FL)]] (AHC/DC)\n| coach_years11 = 2017\u20132018\n| coach_team11 = [[Houston Cougars football|Houston]] (DC/ILB)\n| overall_record = \n| bowl_record =\n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n\n'''Mark Emil D'Onofrio''' (born March 17, 1969) is a former American [[college football]] coach and former professional player. He was formerly the [[defensive coordinator]] and inside linebackers coach for the [[Houston Cougars football|University of Houston]].<ref>[http://www.chron.com/sports/cougars/article/UH-Major-Applewhite-fill-out-coaching-staff-10840473.php UH, Major Applewhite fill out coaching staff] by Joseph Duarte. ''Houston Chronicle'', 6 January 2017. Retrieved 2017-01-08.</ref>  D'Onofrio played collegiately as a [[linebacker]] at [[Pennsylvania State University]] and thereafter was drafted by the [[Green Bay Packers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL).\n\n==Playing career==\nD'Onofrio played at the collegiate level with the [[Penn State Nittany Lions football|Penn State Nittany Lions]], where he was a team captain. In the [[1992 NFL Draft]], D'Onofrio was selected in the second round by the [[Green Bay Packers]]. He became a starter with the team that season, however a severe injury would cause him to retire soon after.\n\n==Coaching career==\nD'Onofrio's first coaching experience was as linebackers coach at [[Saint Peter's University|Saint Peter's College]]. The next year, he became a defensive assistant with the [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia Bulldogs]]. From there he was a linebackers coach with the [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers Scarlet Knights]] and tight ends, special teams, and inside linebackers coach with the [[Virginia Cavaliers football|Virginia Cavaliers]]. He joined the Temple Owls in 2006 as a defensive coordinator, later being promoted to the Assistant Head Coach/ Defensive Coordinator.\n\nHe followed head coach [[Al Golden (American football)|Al Golden]] to the [[University of Miami]] in the same position he held at Temple for the [[Miami Hurricanes football]] team in December 2010. Al Golden came to Coral Gables to replace Randy Shannon. After Golden was fired in the wake of a 58-0 loss to Clemson, D'Onofrio finished out the 2015 season as defensive coordinator and was then terminated following Miami's SunBowl loss to Washington State, 20-16.<ref>[https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2015/12/26/10667680/washington-state-miami-sun-bowl-recap-final-score-snow] Washington State beats Miami in extremely snowy Sun Bowl, by Peter Burkes. Retrieved 2017-01-09.</ref> He spent 2016 out of football while coaching at the Boys & Girls Club in Miami.\n\nOn January 6, 2017, D'Onofrio was hired by the [[Houston Cougars football|Houston Cougars]] as their [[defensive coordinator]] and inside linebackers coach, beginning with the 2017 season.<ref>[http://www.chron.com/sports/cougars/article/UH-Major-Applewhite-fill-out-coaching-staff-10840473.php UH, Major Applewhite fill out coaching staff] by Joseph Duarte. ''Houston Chronicle'', 6 January 2017. Retrieved 2017-01-08.</ref>\n\nOn November 25, 2018, Major Applewhite announced that D'Onofrio had been relieved of his duties as defensive coordinator at the University of Houston.<ref>[https://www.houstonchronicle.com/sports/cougars/article/Houston-fires-defensive-coordinator-Mark-D-Onofrio-13420314.php UH fires defensive coordinator Mark D'Onofrio] by Joseph Duarte. ''Houston Chronicle'', 25 November 2018. Retrieved 2018-12-23.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Green Bay Packers players]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130812073243/http://www.hurricanesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=28700&ATCLID=205558561 Miami profile]\n\n{{Packers1992DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:D'Onofrio, Mark}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football coaches]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:Houston Cougars football coaches]]\n[[Category:Miami Hurricanes football coaches]]\n[[Category:Penn State Nittany Lions football players]]\n[[Category:Rutgers Scarlet Knights football coaches]]\n[[Category:Saint Peter's Peacocks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Temple Owls football coaches]]\n[[Category:Virginia Cavaliers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hoboken, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Mark D'Onofrio\n| image = Mark D'Onofrio 2012.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = D'Onofrio with the Miami Hurricanes\n| current_record = \n| contract = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1969|03|17}}\n| birth_place = [[Hoboken, New Jersey]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1988\u20131991\n| player_team1 = [[Penn State Nittany Lions football|Penn State]]\n| player_years2 = 1992\n| player_team2 = [[Green Bay Packers]]\n| player_positions = [[Linebacker]]\n| coach_years1 = 1999\n| coach_team1 = [[Saint Peter's Peacocks football|Saint Peter's]] (LB)\n| coach_years2 = 2000\n| coach_team2 = [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] (DA)\n| coach_years3 = 2001\n| coach_team3 = [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]] (LB)\n| coach_years4 = 2002\u20132003\n| coach_team4 = Rutgers (LB/RC)\n| coach_years5 = 2004\n| coach_team5 = [[Virginia Cavaliers football|Virginia]] (TE/ST)\n| coach_years6 = 2005\n| coach_team6 = Virginia (ILB/ST)\n| coach_years7 = 2006\u20132007\n| coach_team7 = [[Temple Owls football|Temple]] (DC)\n| coach_years8 = 2008\u20132009\n| coach_team8 = Temple (AHC/DC)\n| coach_years9 = 2010\n| coach_team9 = Temple (AHC/DC/LB)\n| coach_years10 = 2011\u20132015\n| coach_team10 = [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami (FL)]] (AHC/DC)\n| coach_years11 = 2017\u20132018\n| coach_team11 = [[Houston Cougars football|Houston]] (DC/ILB)\n| overall_record = \n| bowl_record =\n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n\n'''Mark Emil D'Onofrio''' (born March 17, 1969), is a former American [[college football]] coach and former professional player. He was formerly the [[defensive coordinator]] and inside linebackers coach for the [[Houston Cougars football|University of Houston]].<ref>[http://www.chron.com/sports/cougars/article/UH-Major-Applewhite-fill-out-coaching-staff-10840473.php UH, Major Applewhite fill out coaching staff] by Joseph Duarte. ''Houston Chronicle'', 6 January 2017. Retrieved 2017-01-08.</ref>  D'Onofrio played collegiately as a [[linebacker]] at [[Pennsylvania State University]] and thereafter was drafted by the [[Green Bay Packers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL).\n\n==Playing career==\nD'Onofrio played at the collegiate level with the [[Penn State Nittany Lions football|Penn State Nittany Lions]], where he was a team captain. In the [[1992 NFL Draft]], D'Onofrio was selected in the second round by the [[Green Bay Packers]]. He became a starter with the team that season, however a severe injury would cause him to retire soon after.\n\n==Coaching career==\nD'Onofrio's first coaching experience was as linebackers coach at [[Saint Peter's University|Saint Peter's College]]. The next year, he became a defensive assistant with the [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia Bulldogs]]. From there he was a linebackers coach with the [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers Scarlet Knights]] and tight ends, special teams, and inside linebackers coach with the [[Virginia Cavaliers football|Virginia Cavaliers]]. He joined the Temple Owls in 2006 as a defensive coordinator, later being promoted to the Assistant Head Coach/ Defensive Coordinator.\n\nHe followed head coach [[Al Golden (American football)|Al Golden]] to the [[University of Miami]] in the same position he held at Temple for the [[Miami Hurricanes football]] team in December 2010. Al Golden came to Coral Gables to replace Randy Shannon. After Golden was fired in the wake of a 58-0 loss to Clemson, D'Onofrio finished out the 2015 season as defensive coordinator and was then terminated following Miami's SunBowl loss to Washington State, 20-16.<ref>[https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2015/12/26/10667680/washington-state-miami-sun-bowl-recap-final-score-snow] Washington State beats Miami in extremely snowy Sun Bowl, by Peter Burkes. Retrieved 2017-01-09.</ref> He spent 2016 out of football while coaching at the Boys & Girls Club in Miami.\n\nOn January 6, 2017, D'Onofrio was hired by the [[Houston Cougars football|Houston Cougars]] as their [[defensive coordinator]] and inside linebackers coach, beginning with the 2017 season.<ref>[http://www.chron.com/sports/cougars/article/UH-Major-Applewhite-fill-out-coaching-staff-10840473.php UH, Major Applewhite fill out coaching staff] by Joseph Duarte. ''Houston Chronicle'', 6 January 2017. Retrieved 2017-01-08.</ref>\n\nOn November 25, 2018, Major Applewhite announced that D'Onofrio had been relieved of his duties as defensive coordinator at the University of Houston.<ref>[https://www.houstonchronicle.com/sports/cougars/article/Houston-fires-defensive-coordinator-Mark-D-Onofrio-13420314.php UH fires defensive coordinator Mark D'Onofrio] by Joseph Duarte. ''Houston Chronicle'', 25 November 2018. Retrieved 2018-12-23.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Green Bay Packers players]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130812073243/http://www.hurricanesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=28700&ATCLID=205558561 Miami profile]\n\n{{Packers1992DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:D'Onofrio, Mark}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football coaches]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:Houston Cougars football coaches]]\n[[Category:Miami Hurricanes football coaches]]\n[[Category:Penn State Nittany Lions football players]]\n[[Category:Rutgers Scarlet Knights football coaches]]\n[[Category:Saint Peter's Peacocks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Temple Owls football coaches]]\n[[Category:Virginia Cavaliers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Hoboken, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Jweiss11", "label": "safe", "comment": "rem comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_D%27Onofrio"}
{"title_page": "Jade City (novel)", "text_new": "{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name          = Jade City\n| image         = JadeCity.jpg\n| caption       = Softcover edition\n| author        = [[Fonda Lee]]\n| language      = English\n| genre         = [[Fantasy]]\n| publisher     = [[Orbit Books|Orbit]]\n| release_date  = November 7, 2017\n| media_type    = Print, e-book\n| pages         = 560\n| awards        = [[World Fantasy Award\u2014Novel|World Fantasy Award]] (2018)\n| isbn          = 978-0316440882\n| series        = [[Green Bone Saga]]\n| followed_by   = [[Jade War]]\n}}\n\n'''''Jade City''''' is a 2017 [[Gangster film|gangster]] [[fantasy]] novel by [[Fonda Lee]].<ref name=\"Lee2017\">{{cite book | last = Lee | first = Fonda | title = Jade city | publisher = Orbit/Hachette Book Group | location = New York, NY | year = 2017 | isbn = 9780316440882 }}</ref> It won the [[World Fantasy Award]] in 2018<ref name=\"WFA2018\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tor.com/2018/11/04/announcing-the-2018-world-fantasy-award-winners/ |title=Announcing the 2018 World Fantasy Award Winners |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=November 4, 2018 |website=tor.com |access-date=April 26, 2019}}</ref> and is the first in the Green Bone Saga trilogy.\n\n==Setting and inspiration==\nLee describes the novel as \"[[The Godfather (novel)|''The Godfather'']] with magic and kung fu\"<ref name=\"LeeReddit\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/Fantasy/comments/7g4voa/im_fonda_lee_author_of_jade_city_ask_me_anything/ |title=I'm Fonda Lee, author of JADE CITY. Ask Me Anything! |last=Lee |first=Fonda |website=reddit.com}}</ref> and cites her love of [[wuxia]] and [[gangster film]]s as inspirations.\n\nThe titular Jade City is a nickname for Janloon, the capital of the island of Kekon in the novel's [[High fantasy|secondary world]] setting. One reviewer described Kekon as \"an analog of mid-20th-century Hong Kong\" <ref name=\"Kirkus\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/fonda-lee/jade-city-the-green-bone-saga/ |title=Jade City by Fonda Lee |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=November 7, 2017 |publisher=[[Kirkus Reviews]]}}</ref> although Lee has alluded to the setting being inspired by Asia more generally, stating that Kekon is not \"Hong Kong or Taiwan or Japan or China or any of those places.\" <ref name=\"LeeReddit\"></ref> She has stated that one of her goals for the novel was to \"write an epic fantasy that was not set in medieval Europe,\" featuring \"the scheming and politics and clash of noble houses elements\" in a \"different cultural setting but also different time period.\" <ref name=\"InkToFilm 67\">{{cite podcast |title=Ep-67 The Godfather (1972 film) ft. Fonda Lee |website=Ink to Film Podcast |date=November 29, 2018 |url=https://www.inktofilm.com/episodes/2018/11/29/ep-67-the-godfather-1972-film-ft-fonda-lee |access-date=May 27, 2019 |time=1:23.37 |timecaption=Discussion occurs after}}</ref>\n\n===Clans===\n\nThe events of ''Jade City'' take place a generation after the end of the Many Nations War, a conflict roughly analogous to [[World War II]], during which the One Mountain Society, a national liberation movement, successfully fought to end foreign occupation of Kekon. After the war, a dispute over opening Kekon to international trade led to the One Mountain Society disintegrating into a number of rival clans, with the most powerful being the isolationist Mountain clan led by the Ayt family and the internationalist No Peak clan led by the Kaul family.\n\nThe organization of the clans is similar to the crime families in ''The Godfather'', in which the Corleone family has a [[Crime boss|don]], [[underboss]] and ''[[consigliere]]''; the clans each have a Pillar, Horn and Weather Man. The Pillar is the head of the clan, the Horn leads its street fighters and the Weather Man is responsible for business activities.\n\nThe Horn oversees the clan's Fists, who each command a number of Fingers, similar to [[Caporegime]]s and [[Soldato|soldier]]s in the [[American Mafia]]. Unlike in the Mafia, the Weather Man manages an office in the business district, staffed by clan members known as Luckbringers.\n\nOutside of the family but still part of the clan are the Lantern Men, business owners who were civilian accomplices in the liberation movement. After the war they began to pay financial tribute to the clans in return for [[Protection racket|protection]] from criminal gangs of untrained jade users.\n\nClan members who wear jade are known as Green Bones. They are governed by the aisho honor code, which prevents them from killing unjaded family members of their enemies except in very specific circumstances (clan informants who wear no jade are known as White Rats, and can be killed without violating aisho).\n\n===Jade===\n\nKekon contains the world's only supply of jade, a mineral that endows its wearer with enhanced abilities. Safe use of jade requires a combination of genetic predisposition and intense training in the six disciplines of Strength, Steel, Perception, Lightness, Deflection and Channelling.\n\nBefore writing ''Jade City'', Lee received an MBA from Stanford, worked as a business strategist and wrote science fiction novels.<ref name=\"LeeLocus\">{{cite web |url=https://locusmag.com/2018/07/fonda-lee-when-the-alien-invaders-win/ |title=Fonda Lee: When the Alien Invaders Win |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=July 16, 2018 }}</ref> She has stated that she \"[treats] the magic almost in a science fictional way\" and as \"a way to have the international trade and politics play out in the storyline.\"<ref name=\"InkToFilm 68\">{{cite podcast |title=Ep-68 The Godfather part II (1974 film) ft. Fonda Lee |website=Ink to Film Podcast |date=December 6, 2018 |url=https://www.inktofilm.com/episodes/2018/12/6/ep-68-the-godfather-part-ii-1974-film-ft-fonda-lee |access-date=May 27, 2019 |time=82:17 |timecaption=Discussion occurs after}}</ref> Jade is the only magical element in the novel, and while the Kekonese regard it as having mystical properties, the Westerners refer to it as \"bioenergetic jade,\" something explicable by science.\n\nAn individual's response to jade is determined by their genetic makeup. The aboriginal population of Kekon, the Abukei, are completely immune to its effects, while individuals from outside Kekon are too sensitive to it. Only the Kekonese, with mixed aboriginal and settler ancestry, have the necessary combination of resistance and sensitivity to be able to use it long-term, although there are wide variations in jade ability among the population, for reasons not well understood. In addition, some Kekonese are born with a recessive genetic trait that makes them immune to jade. These individuals are known as \"stone-eyes\", and are considered unlucky by other Kekonese. Lee has commented that she tied jade ability to a combination of genetics and luck as \"a way to subvert that trope of the blood talent... the chosen ones.\"<ref name=\"InkToFilm 68\" />\n\nKekonese jade users have to spend years in training at the clan academies to use it safely. Overexposure to jade leads to The Itches, a condition causing madness and eventual death. Jade tolerance can also be increased through injections of a drug called SN1 or \"shine.\" Shine is used as a medicine to treat Green Bones, and in addition is traded on the black market and used illicitly by Kekonese who want to wear jade but who do not have academy training. It is also used outside Kekon to facilitate military use of jade by non-Kekonese troops.\n\nUse and production of Jade on Kekon is governed by various traditions and institutions. Green Bones are entitled to claim the jade from enemies they kill in combat. Jade use is supposed to be kept out of government, so members of the Royal Council of Kekon, a representative assembly with lawmaking powers, are banned from wearing it. Jade mining is overseen by the Kekon Jade Alliance (KJA), a private business consortium whose shares are split between the clans. The KJA makes allocations of jade to various organizations including the temples of Deitism, Kekon's main religion, where it is used in rituals.\n\n==Characters==\n\n===No Peak clan===\n\n* '''Lan''' (Kaul Lanshinwan): The recently-anointed Pillar, inheriting the role from his grandfather Kaul Sen. Lan's wife recently left him for another man, causing him to lose face in Kekon and affecting his confidence in his abilities. Despite this, he strives to be a strong leader for the clan.\n\n* '''Hilo''' (Kaul Hiloshudon): Horn and brother of the Pillar, a big-hearted, hot-headed street fighter who commands absolute loyalty from his subordinates.\n\n* '''Shae''' (Kaul Shaelinsan): The third Kaul sibling, Shae holds no position in the clan and wears no jade by choice, despite having completed her training at the Academy. After the breakup of her relationship with a non-Kekonese soldier, Shae returns to Kekon looking for a job outside the clan where she can put her foreign education to use.\n\n* '''Kaul Sen''' (Kaul Seningtun): Original clan Pillar, known as the Torch of Kekon for his actions during the battle for independence. Now retired and slipping into dementia, he is a shadow of the man he once was.\n\n* '''Kaul Wan Ria''' (Kaul Wan Riamasan) Daughter-in-law of Kaul Sen and mother of the Kaul siblings. Her husband died in the war and she takes no part in clan affairs.\n\n* '''Doru''' (Yun Dorupon): The aged, calculating Weather Man of No Peak, increasingly at odds with the younger generation now in charge of the clan.\n\n* '''Anden''' (Emery Anden): Adopted grandson of Kaul Sen, he is in his final year as a student at the Academy.\n\n* '''Wen''' (Maik Wenruxian): Sister of two prominent Fists of the No Peak clan, she is in a relationship with Hilo. She is a stone-eye.\n\n===Mountain clan===\n\n* '''Ayt Mada''' (Ayt Madashi): Ruthless Pillar who inherited the role by murdering the other contenders when her adoptive father Ayt Yugontin, the Spear of Kekon, died.\n\n* '''Gont Asch''' (Gont Aschentu): Fearsome, brutish Horn whose physical prowess masks hidden cunning.\n\n* '''Ree Tura''' (Ree Turahuo): Weather Man. Nearing retirement, he is not well-regarded by the Pillar or Horn.\n\n===Unaffiliated===\n\n* '''Bero''': A minor street thief. Despite being untrained, he has ambitions to wear jade and doesn't mind how he gets it.\n\n* '''Mudt''' (Mudt Jindonon): A smuggler and informant who sells Bero's stolen merchandise through his discount goods store.\n\n==Plot==\n\nBero, a minor thief, attempts to steal jade from a No Peak Fist while he is dining in a clan-affiliated restaurant, but Bero and his Abukei accomplice Sampa are quickly caught and brought to Hilo for punishment. After they are beaten, a remark by Sampa about a recent murder in clan territory leads Hilo to take the two boys to be questioned in the presence of his brother Lan, the clan Pillar.\n\nHilo attempts to convince Lan that the Mountain clan is squeezing No Peak territory, but he is opposed by Doru the Weather Man, who suggests it is a misunderstanding and counsels a peaceful solution. Feeling frustrated and unsupported by Doru, Lan asks his grandfather for permission to replace him as Weather Man, but Kaul Sen refuses to allow it. A short time after this, Shae returns to Kekon, looking for a job that will not require her to wear jade.\n\nThe Mountain comes close to violating aisho by kidnapping Anden, who is still in his final year at the Academy. Ayt Mada offers Anden a position in her clan, signalling that she wishes to unite the Mountain and No Peak. Her purpose is partially to send a message that she considers Hilo an unsuitable Horn.\n\nOnce Anden has been returned safely, Lan begins to move against the Mountain. He proposes a new law preventing any one clan from gaining control of the Kekon Jade Alliance, and he sends Shae to audit the KJA's accounts, looking for irregularities.\n\nTheir message to Anden having been disregarded, the Mountain makes an attempt on Hilo's life. In retaliation, No Peak threatens to storm their training complex. To prevent this, the Mountain apologizes, gives up the would-be assassins and makes a territorial concession. The more senior of the assassins offers Lan a clean blade, demanding to be killed in combat. Believing that he needs to prove himself to the clan in order to remain Pillar, Lan accepts and wins the duel, but only barely.\n\nIn the aftermath, Hilo asks his brother for permission to marry his girlfriend Wen, and Lan, despite misgivings about his brother marrying a stone-eye from a disreputable family, gives his permission.\n\nLan has been injured in the duel and his jade tolerance has been affected, but he cannot be seen to show weakness by failing to wear the additional jade he has won. He arranges for Anden to bring him packages of shine. When Anden realizes what he is delivering he pleads with Lan to stop using the drug, but Lan swears him to secrecy. When Shae comes to see Anden he tries to tell her about the shine, but misses his opportunity.\n\nShae reports to Lan that someone in the KJA is skimming jade, and that either Doru doesn't know about it and is incompetent, or he is allowing it to happen. Lan sends Doru overseas to get him out of the way and tells his allies on the Royal Council that he is going to suspend jade production. Lan receives a letter from his estranged wife, but can't bring himself to open it.\n\nMeanwhile Bero has been stealing shipments from the Docks. Through his fence he meets a mysterious Mountain Green Bone, who gives Bero a submachine gun and tells him to use it to shoot up the gentleman's club Lan frequents. Lan accidentally takes an overdose of shine while visiting the club, and when Bero attacks him he falls into the sea and drowns.\n\nWhen Shae hears about his death she immediately goes to the bank where her jade is kept and puts it all back on. Hilo is now Pillar and she persuades him to strike back by reclaiming some disputed territory rather than launching an all-out attack on the Mountain. She takes part in the battle, fighting several Mountain Green Bones and killing two. Afterward, Hilo asks her to become his Weather Man and she agrees. She cements her position by gaining the support of her main rivals for the role, and she spares Doru's life on condition that he gives up his jade, renounces clan business and spends his remaining days as a companion for her grandfather.\n\nThe clans are now in a state of open war. Shae and Hilo attend negotiations with Ayt Mada and her Weather Man until Hilo accuses the Mountain of skimming jade from the KJA and supplying it to non-Green Bones, then storms out. Ayt arranges to meet Shae on safe ground and tries to talk her into betraying No Peak, but Shae refuses, knowing that she is putting her life in serious jeopardy by doing so. She tells Hilo that No Peak can only hold out for another six months.\n\nWen asks Shae to make her a spy for the clan, without Hilo's knowledge. Shae sends her to a foreign military base with a shipment of jade worth millions, re-establishing the supply that has been disrupted by the KJA's suspension of jade production.\n\nKaul Sen gives his jade to Doru, and Doru uses it to attack his guards and escape, defecting to the Mountain with all his knowledge of No Peak's business dealings. The Mountain continues to use its superior position to maim and kill No Peak Green Bones. On New Year's Day, Hilo marries Wen, then has Anden drive him into Mountain territory to be killed in combat, in return for clemency for the remaining No Peak clan members. Hilo kills several Green Bones but is overwhelmed. When Gont Asch steps in to finish him, Hilo and Anden together kill the Horn of the Mountain.\n\nThe fight leaves Anden in a coma. When he regains consciousness, he learns that the loss of its Horn has dealt the Mountain a serious blow and given No Peak a temporary advantage in the war. Anden returns to the Academy for his graduation ceremony, but when he is presented with his jade he declares he does not want to be a Green Bone. He tells Hilo he does not want a life of violence, and when the Pillar rebukes him Anden runs from the Academy to Lan's grave.\n\nLater, under cover of darkness, Bero also visits the grave. He is still looking for jade, and in the former Pillar's coffin there is a generous supply.\n\n==Reception==\n''Jade City'' won the 2018 [[World Fantasy Award\u2014Novel|World Fantasy Award]] (tied with [[Victor LaValle|Victor LaValle's]] ''The Changeling'') and the [[Aurora Award for Best Novel|Aurora Award]], and was a finalist for the [[Nebula Award for Best Novel|Nebula]] and [[Locus Award for Best Fantasy Novel|Locus Awards]].\n\n''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' called the novel \"an engaging blend of crime drama and Asian martial arts film tropes\"<ref name=\"PublishersWeekly\">{{cite web |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-316-44086-8 |title=Fiction Book Review: Jade City by Fonda Lee |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 8, 2017 |website=[[Publishers Weekly]]}}</ref> and it received a starred review from [[Library Journal]].<ref name=\"LibraryJournal\">{{cite web |url=https://www.libraryjournal.com/?reviewDetail=jade-city |title=Jade City |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=October 15, 2017 |publisher=[[Library Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{World Fantasy Award Best Novel}}\n\n[[Category:2017 American novels]]\n[[Category:2017 fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:World Fantasy Award for Best Novel-winning works]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name          = Jade City\n| image         = JadeCity.jpg\n| caption       = Softcover edition\n| author        = [[Fonda Lee]]\n| language      = English\n| genre         = [[Fantasy]]\n| publisher     = [[Orbit Books|Orbit]]\n| release_date  = November 7, 2017\n| media_type    = Print, e-book\n| pages         = 560\n| awards        = [[World Fantasy Award\u2014Novel|World Fantasy Award]] (2018)\n| isbn          = 978-0316440882\n| series        = [[Green Bone Saga]]\n| followed_by   = [[Jade War]]\n}}\n\n'''''Jade City''''' is a 2017 [[Gangster film|gangster]] [[fantasy]] novel by [[Fonda Lee]].<ref name=\"Lee2017\">{{cite book | last = Lee | first = Fonda | title = Jade city | publisher = Orbit/Hachette Book Group | location = New York, NY | year = 2017 | isbn = 9780316440882 }}</ref> It won the [[World Fantasy Award]] in 2018<ref name=\"WFA2018\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tor.com/2018/11/04/announcing-the-2018-world-fantasy-award-winners/ |title=Announcing the 2018 World Fantasy Award Winners |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=November 4, 2018 |website=tor.com |access-date=April 26, 2019}}</ref> and is the first in the Green Bone Saga trilogy.\n\n==Setting and inspiration==\nLee describes the novel as \"[[The Godfather (novel)|''The Godfather'']] with magic and kung fu\"<ref name=\"LeeReddit\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/Fantasy/comments/7g4voa/im_fonda_lee_author_of_jade_city_ask_me_anything/ |title=I'm Fonda Lee, author of JADE CITY. Ask Me Anything! |last=Lee |first=Fonda |website=reddit.com}}</ref> and cites her love of [[wuxia]] and [[gangster film]]s as inspirations.\n\nThe titular Jade City is a nickname for Janloon, the capital of the island of Kekon in the novel's [[High fantasy|secondary world]] setting. One reviewer described Kekon as \"an analog of mid-20th-century Hong Kong\" <ref name=\"Kirkus\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/fonda-lee/jade-city-the-green-bone-saga/ |title=Jade City by Fonda Lee |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=November 7, 2017 |publisher=[[Kirkus Reviews]]}}</ref> although Lee has alluded to the setting being inspired by Asia more generally, stating that Kekon is not \"Hong Kong or Taiwan or Japan or China or any of those places.\" <ref name=\"LeeReddit\"></ref> She has stated that one of her goals for the novel was to \"write an epic fantasy that was not set in medieval Europe,\" featuring \"the scheming and politics and clash of noble houses elements\" in a \"different cultural setting but also different time period.\" <ref name=\"InkToFilm 67\">{{cite podcast |title=Ep-67 The Godfather (1972 film) ft. Fonda Lee |website=Ink to Film Podcast |date=November 29, 2018 |url=https://www.inktofilm.com/episodes/2018/11/29/ep-67-the-godfather-1972-film-ft-fonda-lee |access-date=May 27, 2019 |time=1:23.37 |timecaption=Discussion occurs after}}</ref>\n\n===Clans===\n\nThe events of ''Jade City'' take place a generation after the end of the Many Nations War, a conflict roughly analogous to [[World War II]], during which the One Mountain Society, a national liberation movement, successfully fought to end foreign occupation of Kekon. After the war, a dispute over opening Kekon to international trade led to the One Mountain Society disintegrating into a number of rival clans, with the most powerful being the isolationist Mountain clan led by the Ayt family and the internationalist No Peak clan led by the Kaul family.\n\nThe organization of the clans is similar to the crime families in ''The Godfather'', in which the Corleone family has a [[Crime boss|don]], [[underboss]] and [[''consigliere'']]; the clans each have a Pillar, Horn and Weather Man. The Pillar is the head of the clan, the Horn leads its street fighters and the Weather Man is responsible for business activities.\n\nThe Horn oversees the clan's Fists, who each command a number of Fingers, similar to [[Caporegime]]s and [[Soldato|soldier]]s in the [[American Mafia]]. Unlike in the Mafia, the Weather Man manages an office in the business district, staffed by clan members known as Luckbringers.\n\nOutside of the family but still part of the clan are the Lantern Men, business owners who were civilian accomplices in the liberation movement. After the war they began to pay financial tribute to the clans in return for [[Protection racket|protection]] from criminal gangs of untrained jade users.\n\nClan members who wear jade are known as Green Bones. They are governed by the aisho honor code, which prevents them from killing unjaded family members of their enemies except in very specific circumstances (clan informants who wear no jade are known as White Rats, and can be killed without violating aisho).\n\n===Jade===\n\nKekon contains the world's only supply of jade, a mineral that endows its wearer with enhanced abilities. Safe use of jade requires a combination of genetic predisposition and intense training in the six disciplines of Strength, Steel, Perception, Lightness, Deflection and Channelling.\n\nBefore writing ''Jade City'', Lee received an MBA from Stanford, worked as a business strategist and wrote science fiction novels.<ref name=\"LeeLocus\">{{cite web |url=https://locusmag.com/2018/07/fonda-lee-when-the-alien-invaders-win/ |title=Fonda Lee: When the Alien Invaders Win |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=July 16, 2018 }}</ref> She has stated that she \"[treats] the magic almost in a science fictional way\" and as \"a way to have the international trade and politics play out in the storyline.\"<ref name=\"InkToFilm 68\">{{cite podcast |title=Ep-68 The Godfather part II (1974 film) ft. Fonda Lee |website=Ink to Film Podcast |date=December 6, 2018 |url=https://www.inktofilm.com/episodes/2018/12/6/ep-68-the-godfather-part-ii-1974-film-ft-fonda-lee |access-date=May 27, 2019 |time=82:17 |timecaption=Discussion occurs after}}</ref> Jade is the only magical element in the novel, and while the Kekonese regard it as having mystical properties, the Westerners refer to it as \"bioenergetic jade,\" something explicable by science.\n\nAn individual's response to jade is determined by their genetic makeup. The aboriginal population of Kekon, the Abukei, are completely immune to its effects, while individuals from outside Kekon are too sensitive to it. Only the Kekonese, with mixed aboriginal and settler ancestry, have the necessary combination of resistance and sensitivity to be able to use it long-term, although there are wide variations in jade ability among the population, for reasons not well understood. In addition, some Kekonese are born with a recessive genetic trait that makes them immune to jade. These individuals are known as \"stone-eyes\", and are considered unlucky by other Kekonese. Lee has commented that she tied jade ability to a combination of genetics and luck as \"a way to subvert that trope of the blood talent... the chosen ones.\"<ref name=\"InkToFilm 68\" />\n\nKekonese jade users have to spend years in training at the clan academies to use it safely. Overexposure to jade leads to The Itches, a condition causing madness and eventual death. Jade tolerance can also be increased through injections of a drug called SN1 or \"shine.\" Shine is used as a medicine to treat Green Bones, and in addition is traded on the black market and used illicitly by Kekonese who want to wear jade but who do not have academy training. It is also used outside Kekon to facilitate military use of jade by non-Kekonese troops.\n\nUse and production of Jade on Kekon is governed by various traditions and institutions. Green Bones are entitled to claim the jade from enemies they kill in combat. Jade use is supposed to be kept out of government, so members of the Royal Council of Kekon, a representative assembly with lawmaking powers, are banned from wearing it. Jade mining is overseen by the Kekon Jade Alliance (KJA), a private business consortium whose shares are split between the clans. The KJA makes allocations of jade to various organizations including the temples of Deitism, Kekon's main religion, where it is used in rituals.\n\n==Characters==\n\n===No Peak clan===\n\n* '''Lan''' (Kaul Lanshinwan): The recently-anointed Pillar, inheriting the role from his grandfather Kaul Sen. Lan's wife recently left him for another man, causing him to lose face in Kekon and affecting his confidence in his abilities. Despite this, he strives to be a strong leader for the clan.\n\n* '''Hilo''' (Kaul Hiloshudon): Horn and brother of the Pillar, a big-hearted, hot-headed street fighter who commands absolute loyalty from his subordinates.\n\n* '''Shae''' (Kaul Shaelinsan): The third Kaul sibling, Shae holds no position in the clan and wears no jade by choice, despite having completed her training at the Academy. After the breakup of her relationship with a non-Kekonese soldier, Shae returns to Kekon looking for a job outside the clan where she can put her foreign education to use.\n\n* '''Kaul Sen''' (Kaul Seningtun): Original clan Pillar, known as the Torch of Kekon for his actions during the battle for independence. Now retired and slipping into dementia, he is a shadow of the man he once was.\n\n* '''Kaul Wan Ria''' (Kaul Wan Riamasan) Daughter-in-law of Kaul Sen and mother of the Kaul siblings. Her husband died in the war and she takes no part in clan affairs.\n\n* '''Doru''' (Yun Dorupon): The aged, calculating Weather Man of No Peak, increasingly at odds with the younger generation now in charge of the clan.\n\n* '''Anden''' (Emery Anden): Adopted grandson of Kaul Sen, he is in his final year as a student at the Academy.\n\n* '''Wen''' (Maik Wenruxian): Sister of two prominent Fists of the No Peak clan, she is in a relationship with Hilo. She is a stone-eye.\n\n===Mountain clan===\n\n* '''Ayt Mada''' (Ayt Madashi): Ruthless Pillar who inherited the role by murdering the other contenders when her adoptive father Ayt Yugontin, the Spear of Kekon, died.\n\n* '''Gont Asch''' (Gont Aschentu): Fearsome, brutish Horn whose physical prowess masks hidden cunning.\n\n* '''Ree Tura''' (Ree Turahuo): Weather Man. Nearing retirement, he is not well-regarded by the Pillar or Horn.\n\n===Unaffiliated===\n\n* '''Bero''': A minor street thief. Despite being untrained, he has ambitions to wear jade and doesn't mind how he gets it.\n\n* '''Mudt''' (Mudt Jindonon): A smuggler and informant who sells Bero's stolen merchandise through his discount goods store.\n\n==Plot==\n\nBero, a minor thief, attempts to steal jade from a No Peak Fist while he is dining in a clan-affiliated restaurant, but Bero and his Abukei accomplice Sampa are quickly caught and brought to Hilo for punishment. After they are beaten, a remark by Sampa about a recent murder in clan territory leads Hilo to take the two boys to be questioned in the presence of his brother Lan, the clan Pillar.\n\nHilo attempts to convince Lan that the Mountain clan is squeezing No Peak territory, but he is opposed by Doru the Weather Man, who suggests it is a misunderstanding and counsels a peaceful solution. Feeling frustrated and unsupported by Doru, Lan asks his grandfather for permission to replace him as Weather Man, but Kaul Sen refuses to allow it. A short time after this, Shae returns to Kekon, looking for a job that will not require her to wear jade.\n\nThe Mountain comes close to violating aisho by kidnapping Anden, who is still in his final year at the Academy. Ayt Mada offers Anden a position in her clan, signalling that she wishes to unite the Mountain and No Peak. Her purpose is partially to send a message that she considers Hilo an unsuitable Horn.\n\nOnce Anden has been returned safely, Lan begins to move against the Mountain. He proposes a new law preventing any one clan from gaining control of the Kekon Jade Alliance, and he sends Shae to audit the KJA's accounts, looking for irregularities.\n\nTheir message to Anden having been disregarded, the Mountain makes an attempt on Hilo's life. In retaliation, No Peak threatens to storm their training complex. To prevent this, the Mountain apologizes, gives up the would-be assassins and makes a territorial concession. The more senior of the assassins offers Lan a clean blade, demanding to be killed in combat. Believing that he needs to prove himself to the clan in order to remain Pillar, Lan accepts and wins the duel, but only barely.\n\nIn the aftermath, Hilo asks his brother for permission to marry his girlfriend Wen, and Lan, despite misgivings about his brother marrying a stone-eye from a disreputable family, gives his permission.\n\nLan has been injured in the duel and his jade tolerance has been affected, but he cannot be seen to show weakness by failing to wear the additional jade he has won. He arranges for Anden to bring him packages of shine. When Anden realizes what he is delivering he pleads with Lan to stop using the drug, but Lan swears him to secrecy. When Shae comes to see Anden he tries to tell her about the shine, but misses his opportunity.\n\nShae reports to Lan that someone in the KJA is skimming jade, and that either Doru doesn't know about it and is incompetent, or he is allowing it to happen. Lan sends Doru overseas to get him out of the way and tells his allies on the Royal Council that he is going to suspend jade production. Lan receives a letter from his estranged wife, but can't bring himself to open it.\n\nMeanwhile Bero has been stealing shipments from the Docks. Through his fence he meets a mysterious Mountain Green Bone, who gives Bero a submachine gun and tells him to use it to shoot up the gentleman's club Lan frequents. Lan accidentally takes an overdose of shine while visiting the club, and when Bero attacks him he falls into the sea and drowns.\n\nWhen Shae hears about his death she immediately goes to the bank where her jade is kept and puts it all back on. Hilo is now Pillar and she persuades him to strike back by reclaiming some disputed territory rather than launching an all-out attack on the Mountain. She takes part in the battle, fighting several Mountain Green Bones and killing two. Afterward, Hilo asks her to become his Weather Man and she agrees. She cements her position by gaining the support of her main rivals for the role, and she spares Doru's life on condition that he gives up his jade, renounces clan business and spends his remaining days as a companion for her grandfather.\n\nThe clans are now in a state of open war. Shae and Hilo attend negotiations with Ayt Mada and her Weather Man until Hilo accuses the Mountain of skimming jade from the KJA and supplying it to non-Green Bones, then storms out. Ayt arranges to meet Shae on safe ground and tries to talk her into betraying No Peak, but Shae refuses, knowing that she is putting her life in serious jeopardy by doing so. She tells Hilo that No Peak can only hold out for another six months.\n\nWen asks Shae to make her a spy for the clan, without Hilo's knowledge. Shae sends her to a foreign military base with a shipment of jade worth millions, re-establishing the supply that has been disrupted by the KJA's suspension of jade production.\n\nKaul Sen gives his jade to Doru, and Doru uses it to attack his guards and escape, defecting to the Mountain with all his knowledge of No Peak's business dealings. The Mountain continues to use its superior position to maim and kill No Peak Green Bones. On New Year's Day, Hilo marries Wen, then has Anden drive him into Mountain territory to be killed in combat, in return for clemency for the remaining No Peak clan members. Hilo kills several Green Bones but is overwhelmed. When Gont Asch steps in to finish him, Hilo and Anden together kill the Horn of the Mountain.\n\nThe fight leaves Anden in a coma. When he regains consciousness, he learns that the loss of its Horn has dealt the Mountain a serious blow and given No Peak a temporary advantage in the war. Anden returns to the Academy for his graduation ceremony, but when he is presented with his jade he declares he does not want to be a Green Bone. He tells Hilo he does not want a life of violence, and when the Pillar rebukes him Anden runs from the Academy to Lan's grave.\n\nLater, under cover of darkness, Bero also visits the grave. He is still looking for jade, and in the former Pillar's coffin there is a generous supply.\n\n==Reception==\n''Jade City'' won the 2018 [[World Fantasy Award\u2014Novel|World Fantasy Award]] (tied with [[Victor LaValle|Victor LaValle's]] ''The Changeling'') and the [[Aurora Award for Best Novel|Aurora Award]], and was a finalist for the [[Nebula Award for Best Novel|Nebula]] and [[Locus Award for Best Fantasy Novel|Locus Awards]].\n\n''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' called the novel \"an engaging blend of crime drama and Asian martial arts film tropes\"<ref name=\"PublishersWeekly\">{{cite web |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-316-44086-8 |title=Fiction Book Review: Jade City by Fonda Lee |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 8, 2017 |website=[[Publishers Weekly]]}}</ref> and it received a starred review from [[Library Journal]].<ref name=\"LibraryJournal\">{{cite web |url=https://www.libraryjournal.com/?reviewDetail=jade-city |title=Jade City |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=October 15, 2017 |publisher=[[Library Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{World Fantasy Award Best Novel}}\n\n[[Category:2017 American novels]]\n[[Category:2017 fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:World Fantasy Award for Best Novel-winning works]]\n", "name_user": "Julietdeltalima", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClans:WP:TWWPK", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jade_City_(novel)"}
{"title_page": "Anabelle Acosta", "text_new": "{{short description|Cuban-born American actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Anabelle Acosta\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Anabelle Acosta\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1987|02|28}}<ref>[http://scanfigus.com/anabelle-acosta-wiki-bio-age-boyfriend-dating-height.html Biographie Annabelle Acosta]</ref>\n| birth_place   = [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]\n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 2008\u2013present\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Anabelle Acosta''' is a [[Cuba]]n-born American actress. She is best known for playing the roles of Annabella in the [[HBO]] television series ''[[Ballers]]'' and Natalie Vasquez in the [[ABC Studios|ABC]] television series ''[[Quantico (TV series)|Quantico]]''.\n\n== Career ==\n\nIn 2015, Acosta played the recurring role of Annabella in the [[HBO]]'s comedy series ''[[Ballers]]'', she played the role of the girlfriend of Ricky Jerret, played by [[John David Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ooitz|first=Erik|title=Anabelle Acosta hangs with the big boys on new HBO series \u2018Ballers\u2019|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/anabelle-acosta-hangs-big-boys-hbo-ballers-article-1.2257927|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAcosta starred as [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] recruit Natalie Vasquez in [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s thriller series ''[[Quantico (TV series)|Quantico]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Anabelle Acosta Upped To Regular On ABC\u2019s \u2018Quantico\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/anabelle-acosta-promoted-series-regular-quantico-1201514522/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=July2015Variety>{{cite journal|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|title=\u2018Ballers\u2019 Actress Joins ABC\u2019s \u2018Quantico\u2019 in Major Arc|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/quantico-anabelle-acosta-cast-abc-1201540412/|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=July 15, 2015|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nIn 2018, she began dating former ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' actor and current ''[[S.W.A.T. (2017 TV series)|S.W.A.T.]]'' actor [[Shemar Moore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/310778/s-w-a-t-star-shemar-moore-opens-up-about-his-relationship-with-quantico-actress-anabelle-acosta/|title=\u2018S.W.A.T.\u2019 Star Shemar Moore Opens Up About His Relationship With \u2018Quantico\u2019 Actress Anabelle Acosta|last=West|first=Rachel|date=2018-03-20|website=ET Canada|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\nLater on in 2018, she rekindled a past relationship with a Dominican actor, Algenis P\u00e9rez Soto. They married in 2019.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Next Hit]]''\n| Hot Bartender\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2012\n| ''[[Freelancers (film)|Freelancers]]''\n| Cyn\n|-\n| ''Construction''\n| Lori\n|-\n| ''We Made This Movie''\n| Kelly Acevedo\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[By the Gun]]''\n| FBI Agent Sarah Ramsey \n|-\n| 2017\n| [[Fat Camp]]\n| Abby\n|-\n| 2019\n|[[Kill Chain (2019 film)|Kill Chain]]\n| The Woman in Red\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Grace''\n| Eden Grace\n| TV movie\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012\n| ''[[Breaking In (TV series)|Breaking In]]''\n| Phoebe\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[GCB (TV series)|GCB]]''\n| Lucia\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2013\n| ''[[Second Generation Wayans]]''\n| Destiny\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Perception (U.S. TV series)|Perception]]''\n| Eva\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2014\n| ''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]''\n| Maritza\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]''\n| Holly\n| Episode: \"Law & Boarder\"\n|-\n| 2015 - 2016\n| ''[[Ballers]]''\n| Annabella\n| Recurring role; 7 episodes\n|-\n| 2015\u20132016\n| ''[[Quantico (TV series)|Quantico]]''\n| Natalie Vasquez\n| Main role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n|''[[The Arrangement (2017 TV series)|The Arrangement]]''\n|Amelia Briggs / Jaq\n| Recurring role; 3 episodes\n|-\n|''[[Chicago P.D. (TV series)|Chicago P.D.]]''\n|Camila Vega \n| Recurring role\n|-\n|2019\n|[[God Friended Me]]\n|Denise\n|Episode: \"Miracle in 123rd Street\"\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|4166320}}\n* {{Instagram | anabelleacosta1 }}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Acosta, Anabelle}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Havana]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:Cuban film actresses]]\n[[Category:Cuban television actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Cuban actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cuban-born American actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Anabelle Acosta\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Anabelle Acosta\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1987|02|28}}<ref>[http://scanfigus.com/anabelle-acosta-wiki-bio-age-boyfriend-dating-height.html Biographie Annabelle Acosta]</ref>\n| birth_place   = [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]\n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 2008\u2013present\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Anabelle Acosta''' is a [[Cuba]]n-born American actress. She is best known for playing the roles of Annabella in the [[HBO]] television series ''[[Ballers]]'' and Natalie Vasquez in the [[ABC Studios|ABC]] television series ''[[Quantico (TV series)|Quantico]]''.\n\n== Career ==\n\nIn 2015, Acosta played the recurring role of Annabella in the [[HBO]]'s comedy series ''[[Ballers]]'', she played the role of the girlfriend of Ricky Jerret, played by [[John David Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ooitz|first=Erik|title=Anabelle Acosta hangs with the big boys on new HBO series \u2018Ballers\u2019|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/anabelle-acosta-hangs-big-boys-hbo-ballers-article-1.2257927|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAcosta starred as [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] recruit Natalie Vasquez in [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s thriller series ''[[Quantico (TV series)|Quantico]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Anabelle Acosta Upped To Regular On ABC\u2019s \u2018Quantico\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2015/09/anabelle-acosta-promoted-series-regular-quantico-1201514522/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=September 4, 2015|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=July2015Variety>{{cite journal|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|title=\u2018Ballers\u2019 Actress Joins ABC\u2019s \u2018Quantico\u2019 in Major Arc|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/quantico-anabelle-acosta-cast-abc-1201540412/|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=July 15, 2015|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nIn 2018, she began dating former ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' actor and current ''[[S.W.A.T. (2017 TV series)|S.W.A.T.]]'' actor [[Shemar Moore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/310778/s-w-a-t-star-shemar-moore-opens-up-about-his-relationship-with-quantico-actress-anabelle-acosta/|title=\u2018S.W.A.T.\u2019 Star Shemar Moore Opens Up About His Relationship With \u2018Quantico\u2019 Actress Anabelle Acosta|last=West|first=Rachel|date=2018-03-20|website=ET Canada|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\nLater on in 2018, she rekindled a past relationship with a Dominican actor, Algenis P\u00e9rez Soto. They married in 2019.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Next Hit]]''\n| Hot Bartender\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2012\n| ''[[Freelancers (film)|Freelancers]]''\n| Cyn\n|-\n| ''Construction''\n| Lori\n|-\n| ''We Made This Movie''\n| Kelly Acevedo\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[By the Gun]]''\n| FBI Agent Sarah Ramsey \n|-\n| 2017\n| [[Fat Camp]]\n| Abby\n|-\n| 2019\n|[[Kill Chain (2019 film)|Kill Chain]]\n| The Woman in Red\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Grace''\n| Eden Grace\n| TV movie\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012\n| ''[[Breaking In (TV series)|Breaking In]]''\n| Phoebe\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[GCB (TV series)|GCB]]''\n| Lucia\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2013\n| ''[[Second Generation Wayans]]''\n| Destiny\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Perception (U.S. TV series)|Perception]]''\n| Eva\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2014\n| ''[[Supernatural (U.S. TV series)|Supernatural]]''\n| Maritza\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]''\n| Holly\n| Episode: \"Law & Boarder\"\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Ballers]]''\n| Annabella\n| Recurring role; 7 episodes\n|-\n| 2015\u20132016\n| ''[[Quantico (TV series)|Quantico]]''\n| Natalie Vasquez\n| Main role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n|''[[The Arrangement (2017 TV series)|The Arrangement]]''\n|Amelia Briggs / Jaq\n| Recurring role; 3 episodes\n|-\n|''[[Chicago P.D. (TV series)|Chicago P.D.]]''\n|Camila Vega \n| Recurring role\n|-\n|2019\n|[[God Friended Me]]\n|Denise\n|Episode: \"Miracle in 123rd Street\"\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|4166320}}\n* {{Instagram | anabelleacosta1 }}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Acosta, Anabelle}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Havana]]\n[[Category:American people of Cuban descent]]\n[[Category:Cuban film actresses]]\n[[Category:Cuban television actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Cuban actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Highly beloved", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anabelle_Acosta"}
{"title_page": "Devra Davis", "text_new": "{{short description|American epidemiologist and writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{update|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Dr.\n| name               = Devra Lee Davis\n| honorific_suffix   = Ph.D.\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  {{birth date and age|1946|06|07}}\n| birth_place        = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| baptised           =  <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        =\n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments          = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| ethnicity          =  <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| citizenship        = \n| education          = {{hlist|[[University of Pittsburgh]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Arts|MA]])}}|[[University of Chicago]] {{small|([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}|[[Johns Hopkins University]] {{small|([[Professional degrees of public health#United States|MPH]])}} }}\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         =  \n| years_active       =               \n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| agent              =\n| known_for          =  Epidemiologist and Writer\n| works              = \n| style              =\n| home_town          = [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| salary             = \n| net_worth          =  <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height             =  <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| weight             =  <!-- \"X kg\", \"X lb\" or \"X st Y lb\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| television         = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| movement           = <!--Women's Suffrage -->\n| opponents          = \n| boards             =\n| religion           =  <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| denomination       =  <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| criminal_charge    =  <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   =\n| criminal_status    = \n| spouse             =  Richard D. Morgenstern\n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n| awards             = \n| website            =  <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module             =\n| module2            = \n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| module6            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n'''Devra Lee Davis,''' (born June 7, 1946) is an [[Americans|American]] [[Epidemiology|epidemiologist]] and writer.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\">{{cite web|url= http://environmentalhealthtrust.org/images/warnings/CurrentDevraLeeDavisResume2011.doc |format= MS Word|title= Curriculum vitae 2011|publisher= Environmental Health Trust|accessdate= August 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDavis works on disease prevention and environmental health factors. She served as the President Clinton appointee to the [[Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation Board]] from 1994 to 1999, having won bipartisan Senate confirmation. She was Founding Director of the Center for Environmental Oncology, the first of its kind in the world, and presently acts as President of Environmental Health Trust, a non-profit organization focusing on drawing attention to man-made health threats. She lectures at American and European universities and her research has been covered in major scientific publications as well as being highlighted on major media outlets like [[CNN]], [[CSPAN]], [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], [[BBC]], and public radio.<ref name=\"Huffington Post\">{{cite web|url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/devra-davis-phd/| title=Huffington Post, Devra Davis Bio }}</ref><ref name=\"Healthy Child\">{{cite web|url= http://healthychild.org/about-us/devra-davis-phd-mph/|title= Healthy Child, Devra Davis Bio|access-date= December 11, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170612082232/http://www.healthychild.org/about-us/devra-davis-phd-mph/|archive-date= June 12, 2017|url-status= dead}}</ref> In recent years, her attention has become focused on the health hazards of exposures to man-made sources of electromagnetic radiation, especially those from [[wireless devices]].\n\nShe has also authored more than 190 publications in books and journals ranging from ''[[The Lancet]]'' and the ''[[Journal of the American Medical Association]]'' to ''[[Scientific American]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'', and writes for blogs such as [[Freakonomics#Freakonomics blog|Freakonomics]] in the ''New York Times'', in ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', and elsewhere.<ref name=\"EHT_About\">{{cite web|url= http://environmentalhealthtrust.org/about-dr-davis/|title= About Dr. Davis|publisher= Environmental Health Trust|accessdate= August 14, 2012|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120813071902/http://environmentalhealthtrust.org/about-dr-davis/|archive-date= August 13, 2012|url-status= dead}}</ref> She co-founded the Environmental Health Trust in 2007,<ref name=\"EHT_About\" /> with [[David Servan-Schreiber]].{{Citation needed|date= December 2014}}\n\n==Education==\nDavis  received a [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] and an MA from the [[University of Pittsburgh]] in 1967,<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> where she held National Science Foundation fellowships as an honors undergraduate and graduate student. A former Scholar in Residence at the [[National Academy of Sciences]], she completed her [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in science studies at the [[University of Chicago]] as a Danforth Fellow, and a [[Master of Public Health|MPH]] at [[Johns Hopkins University]] as a National Cancer Institute post-doctoral fellow.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> She held post-doctoral positions with the [[National Science Foundation]]; in the history, sociology, and philosophy of science at [[Catholic University]] in 1971; and with the World Man Fund and Lorenz K Y Ng, MD at the [[National Institutes of Health]] between 1975 and 1976.\n\n==Professional life==\nFrom 1970 to 1976, Davis was assistant professor of sociology at [[Queens College]] of City University of New York. Between 1982 and 2002, she was a faculty associate at [[Johns Hopkins University]], Department of Health Policy and Management, School of Hygiene and Public Health.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> She has held a number of posts at universities around the world, and {{As of|2011|lc=y}} was Senior Distinguished Visiting Research Scholar in the [[WHO Collaborating Centres|WHO Collaborating Center for Capacity Building in Public Health]] at Hebrew University, Hadassah School of Public Health and Community Medicine.\n\nOther previous positions are as follows:\n* 1985 Visiting Professor, Environmental Medicine, University of Madrid\n* 1989 Visiting Scholar, Unit of Occupational and Environmental Medicine, School of Public Health, [[Hebrew University]]\n* 1994\u20131999 Senior Scientist, [[Strang Cornell Cancer Prevention Center]], New York City\n* 1996-97 Gotteman Distinguished Professor, [[Stern College for Women]] of [[Yeshiva University]], New York City\n* 2000\u20132004 Visiting Professor, H. John Heinz III School of Public Policy and Management, [[Carnegie Mellon University]], Pittsburgh\n* 2000\u20132004 Honorary Professor, [[London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine]], London, England\n* 2001 Visiting Professor, [[Oberlin College]], Department of Environmental Studies, Oberlin, Ohio\n* 2004\u201310 Professor, Department of Epidemiology, Graduate School of Public Health, [[University of Pittsburgh]]\n\nShe served as a visiting scholar at Hebrew University, School of Public Health, Unit of Occupational and Environmental Medicine in 1989.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/>\n\nShe was the founding director of the Center for Environmental Oncology at the [[University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute]]<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> from 2004 to 2010. The multidisciplinary center included experts in medicine, basic research, engineering, and public policy, who developed cutting-edge studies to identify the causes of cancer and propose policies to reduce the risks of the disease. She was also founding director of the National Academies of Sciences, Board on Environmental Studies and Toxicology of the US National Research Council, from 1983 to 1993, and served as Scholar in Residence from 1990 to 1993.\n\n==Other professional activities==\nA member of both the American Colleges of Toxicology and of Epidemiology,<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> Davis was also a visiting professor in the Department of Environmental and Occupational Medicine at [[Mount Sinai Hospital (Manhattan)|Mt. Sinai Medical Center in New York City]],<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> appointed by [[Irving Selikoff]], a founder of occupational medicine in 1988, until that appointment was terminated by [[Philip Landrigan]] in 2010. In addition, she was a visiting scientist of the Strang Cornell Cancer Prevention Center of [[Rockefeller University]] in 1994.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> She also advised the [[World Health Organization]] in developing its program on environmental health indicators and children's environmental health, and traveled with the [[United Nations Development Program]] to China to advise on programmatic issues.\n\nShe served as a member of the Board of Scientific Counselors of the US National Toxicology Program between 1983 and 1986<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> and was a member of the Presidio Advisory Committee to the US government, and a steering committee member of the Department of Defense Breast Cancer Research Program.\n\nIn 2001, Davis became one of the founders of the [[Green Zionist Alliance|Green Zionist Alliance: The Grassroots Campaign for a Sustainable Israel]]<ref name=\"Green Zionist Alliance\">{{cite news | url=http://www.greenzionism.org/about-us/staff-and-board | title=GZA Co-Founders | work=Green Zionist Alliance }}</ref> and was part of the Green Zionist Alliance slate for elections for the World Zionist Congress in 2002.<ref name=\"gzaSlate2002\">{{cite news | url=http://www.greenzionism.org/en/congress/slates/slate2002 | title=GZA 2002 charter delegate slate for the 34th World Zionist Congress | work=Green Zionist Alliance }}</ref>\n\n===Health of women===\nDavis was Scientific Advisor to the Women's Environment and Development Organization in 1995.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> Davis was also a founding member of the International Breast Cancer Prevention Collaborative Research Group,<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> an organization dedicated to exploring the avoidable causes of breast cancer. She, with Lloyd Morgan and [[Michael Kundi]], reported on unexplained differences in brain tumors between men and women at the annual meeting of the Bioelectromagnetics Society.\n\n===Environment===\nDavis has served on the Board of the Climate Institute,<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> the Coalition of Organizations on the Environment and Jewish Life,<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> and the Earthfire Institute; and is a scientific adviser to the UK registered charity MobileWise.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.mobilewise.org/about-us/our-advisers |title= Our advisors|year= 2011|publisher= MobileWise|accessdate= June 9, 2011}}</ref> She also has advised Green America, Environmental Working Group, the Green Guide, and Healthy Child\u2014non-profit organizations that promote environmental health. She occasionally discusses avoidable environmental health hazards on national and local programming with NPR, Fox News, CNN, ABC, PBS, CBC, BBC,<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> Dutch Public Television, and others.<ref name=\"EHT Home\">{{cite web|url= http://ehtrust.org/home/|title= EHT Home|access-date= December 10, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141213014512/http://ehtrust.org/home/|archive-date= December 13, 2014|url-status= dead}}</ref> She also served as a Lead Author of a chapter on mitigation costs in the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change Third Assessment Report {{cite web|url= http://www.ipcc.ch/ipccreports/tar/wg3/index.php?idp=319|title= IPCC TAR Working Group III: Mitigation }}\n\nShe founded the non-profit Environmental Health Trust in 2007,<ref name=\"EHT_About\" /> with [[David Servan-Schreiber]].{{Citation needed|date= December 2014}}\n\n==Controversies==\nTackling publicly sensitive topics from [[tobacco]], to [[asbestos]] to overuse of diagnostic radiation, Davis's findings and methods have been criticized,<ref>{{Cite web|last= Kinney|first= William H|url= http://www.acsu.buffalo.edu/~whkinney/notevenwrong.html|title= Junk Science: More Research is Needed|accessdate= December 10, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141207221232/http://www.acsu.buffalo.edu/~whkinney/notevenwrong.html|archive-date= December 7, 2014|url-status= dead}}</ref> in some cases being called \"junk science\", especially for raising concerns about [[Wireless device radiation and health|cellphone safety]].<ref>{{cite web|last= Trottier|first= Lorne|author-link= Lorne Trottier|title= A ''Disconnect'' between cell phone fears and science|url= http://www.sciencebasedmedicine.org/a-disconnect-between-cell-phone-fears-and-science/|accessdate= December 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last= Park|first= Bob|author-link= Robert L. Park|title= What's New|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120112021909/http://bobpark.physics.umd.edu/WN10/wn121010.html|date= December 10, 2010|accessdate= December 10, 2014}}</ref> \n\nDavis publicly criticized the prominent epidemiologist Sir [[Richard Doll]], noting in her book ''The Secret History of the War on Cancer'' that his work discovering the link between tobacco and lung cancer in 1955 had been influenced by earlier German studies in the 1930s that he had not acknowledged. [[Richard Horton (editor)|Richard Horton]], editor of ''[[The Lancet]]'', reviewed Davis' work favorably in a lengthy analysis in ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'', taking great exception, however, to her critique of Doll.<ref>{{cite web|last= Horton|first= Richard|author-link= Richard Horton (editor)|title= Cancer: Malignant Maneuvers|url= http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2008/mar/06/cancer-malignant-maneuvers/|date= March 6, 2008|accessdate= December 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nDavis was honored by the Betty Ford Comprehensive Cancer Center and the [[American Cancer Society]] with the Breast Cancer Awareness Award, commended by the Director of the National Cancer Institute for Outstanding Service, and appointed a Global Environmental advisor to ''Newsweek Magazine''.<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/>\n\nShe was a recipient of a Women's Leadership Exchange Compass Award, presented by OPEN: The Small Business Network from [[American Express]], for breaking the paradigms of how women are perceived, Davis received the first Lisa Zhang Environmental Award from the United Nations in July 2008.<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/>\n\nIn June 2009, Davis received the Artemis Award presented by the Euro-American Women's Council and the Greek Foreign Ministry in recognition of her outstanding contributions to science and public health policy.<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> In 2010, she was awarded the Carnegie Science Medal.  In 2012, she received the Lifetime Achievement Award from [[Green America]].<ref name=\"Huffington Post\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenbusinessnetwork.org/news/business-network-news/item/604-campaign-for-safe-cosmetics-devra-davis-win-green-america%E2%80%99s-bea-awards.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923002704/http://www.greenbusinessnetwork.org/news/business-network-news/item/604-campaign-for-safe-cosmetics-devra-davis-win-green-america%E2%80%99s-bea-awards.html|title=Campaign for Safe Cosmetics, Devra Davis Win Green America\u2019s BEA Awards|date=July 17, 2012|archive-date=September 23, 2012|access-date=February 15, 2017|publisher=[[Green America]]|quote=Dr. Devra Davis also received a Lifetime Achievement for her groundbreaking work on the link between cell phone radiation and brain cancer.|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nShe was also awarded the Nautilus Books Silver Medal for Courageous Reporting,<ref name=\"Huffington Post\"/>and chosen by Amazon editors as a top pick of 2014.\n\n==Personal life==\nDavis is married to economist Richard D. Morgenstern. THey live in [[Jackson Hole]], Wyoming, and have five grandchildren.<ref name\"EHT_About_2020\">{{cite web|url= https://ehtrust.org/about/dr-devra-davis/|title= About Dr. Davis|publisher= Environmental Health Trust|access-date= 2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nDavis' books have been translated into Chinese, Turkish, Finnish, Korean, Japanese, and Estonian. She was [[National Book Award]] finalist, for ''When Smoke Ran Like Water'' (2002), which begins with the tale of the [[Donora Smog of 1948]].<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/><ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> \n\nPublications include the following:\n*''Trends in Cancer Mortality in Industrial Countries (Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences)'' (New York Academy of Sciences, 1990). {{ISBN|978-0897666435}}.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/>\n*''Urban Air Pollution Risks to Children: A Global Environmental Health Indicator'' (World Resources Institute, 1999). {{ISBN|978-1569734278}}.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/>\n*''When Smoke Ran Like Water: Tales of Environmental Deception And the Battle Against Pollution''. (Diane Publishing Company, 2002). {{ISBN|978-0465015221}}.\n*''The Secret History of the War on Cancer'' (Basic Books, 2007). {{ISBN|978-0465015689}}.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/>\n*''Disconnect: The Truth About Cell Phone Radiation, What the Industry Has Done to Hide It, and How to Protect Your Family'' (Dutton Adult, 2010; paperback, Plume, 2011; Environmental Health Trust, 2013). {{ISBN|978-0991219902}}. Davis also co-produced a 2014 documentary film, ''Mobilize'', based on the book.<ref>{{cite news|last= Moore|first= Chris|title= Are Cell Phones Really Giving Us Cancer?|url= http://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2014/09/15/are-cell-phones-really-giving-us-cancer/|publisher= CBS Pittsburgh|date= 2014-09-15|access-date= 2017-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Audio recordings==\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=14986010 ''Fresh Air'' interview], October 4, 2007\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080325111838/http://www.writersvoice.net/2008/01/podcast-57-how-everyday-products-make-us-sick/ ''Writer's Voice'' interview], January 2008\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081023214734/http://www.tvo.org/TVO/WebObjects/TVO.woa?video%3FAG_Full_20081003_907694_DevraDavis ''TVO (Ontario)'' interview], October 3, 2008. Length: 26:54\n* Alan Gregg Canada http://allangregg.tvo.org/episode/129397/devra-davis, October 3, 2008\n\n==Mainstream media references==\n* {{cite news|url= http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,2027523,00.html |last= Scherer|first= Michael|title= Cell-Phone Safety: What the FCC Didn't Test|publisher= [[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date= October 26, 2010|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}\n* {{cite web|url= http://magazine.uchicago.edu/1010/features/c-vitae.shtml |first= Ruth E|last= Kott|title= Roaming crusader|work= C. vitae |date=September\u2013October 2010|publisher= University of Chicago Magazine|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Contemporary Authors]] Online. The Gale Group, 2004. PEN (Permanent Entry Number):  0000154775.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.epidemiology.pitt.edu/davis.asp Faculty Bio - Devra Davis] at the Department of Epidemiology, Graduate School of Public Health, University of Pittsburgh\n* [https://ehtrust.org/about/dr-devra-davis/ Devra Davis] at the Environmental Health Trust\n* {{C-SPAN|Devra Davis}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Devra}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:American epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health alumni]]\n[[Category:Women epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:People from Donora, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Taylor Allderdice High School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American epidemiologist and writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{update|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Dr.\n| name               = Devra Lee Davis\n| honorific_suffix   = Ph.D.\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         =  <!-- only use if different from name above -->\n| birth_date         =  {{birth date and age|1946|06|07}}\n| birth_place        = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| baptised           =  <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        =\n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments          = \n| residence          = [[Jackson Hole, Wyoming]], U.S.\n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| ethnicity          =  <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| citizenship        = \n| education          = [[University of Pittsburgh]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Arts|MA]])}} [[University of Chicago]] {{small|([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         =  \n| years_active       =               \n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| agent              =\n| known_for          =  Epidemiologist and Writer\n| works              = \n| style              =\n| home_town          = [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| salary             = \n| net_worth          =  <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height             =  <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\"  or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| weight             =  <!-- \"X kg\", \"X lb\" or \"X st Y lb\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| television         = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| movement           = <!--Women's Suffrage -->\n| opponents          = \n| boards             =\n| religion           =  <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| denomination       =  <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| criminal_charge    =  <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   =\n| criminal_status    = \n| spouse             =  Richard D. Morgenstern\n| partner            =  <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n| awards             = \n| website            =  <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module             =\n| module2            = \n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| module6            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n'''Devra Lee Davis,''' (born June 7, 1946) is an [[Americans|American]] [[Epidemiology|epidemiologist]] and writer.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\">{{cite web|url= http://environmentalhealthtrust.org/images/warnings/CurrentDevraLeeDavisResume2011.doc |format= MS Word|title= Curriculum vitae 2011|publisher= Environmental Health Trust|accessdate= August 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDavis works on disease prevention and environmental health factors. She served as the President Clinton appointee to the [[Chemical Safety and Hazard Investigation Board]] from 1994 to 1999, having won bipartisan Senate confirmation. She was Founding Director of the Center for Environmental Oncology, the first of its kind in the world, and presently acts as President of Environmental Health Trust, a non-profit organization focusing on drawing attention to man-made health threats. She lectures at American and European universities and her research has been covered in major scientific publications as well as being highlighted on major media outlets like [[CNN]], [[CSPAN]], [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], [[BBC]], and public radio.<ref name=\"Huffington Post\">{{cite web|url= http://www.huffingtonpost.com/devra-davis-phd/| title=Huffington Post, Devra Davis Bio }}</ref><ref name=\"Healthy Child\">{{cite web|url= http://healthychild.org/about-us/devra-davis-phd-mph/|title= Healthy Child, Devra Davis Bio|access-date= December 11, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170612082232/http://www.healthychild.org/about-us/devra-davis-phd-mph/|archive-date= June 12, 2017|url-status= dead}}</ref> In recent years, her attention has become focused on the health hazards of exposures to man-made sources of electromagnetic radiation, especially those from [[wireless devices]].\n\nShe has also authored more than 190 publications in books and journals ranging from ''[[The Lancet]]'' and the ''[[Journal of the American Medical Association]]'' to ''[[Scientific American]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'', and writes for blogs such as [[Freakonomics#Freakonomics blog|Freakonomics]] in the ''New York Times'', in ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', and elsewhere.<ref name=\"EHT_About\">{{cite web|url= http://environmentalhealthtrust.org/about-dr-davis/|title= About Dr. Davis|publisher= Environmental Health Trust|accessdate= August 14, 2012|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120813071902/http://environmentalhealthtrust.org/about-dr-davis/|archive-date= August 13, 2012|url-status= dead}}</ref> She co-founded the Environmental Health Trust in 2007,<ref name=\"EHT_About\" /> with [[David Servan-Schreiber]].{{Citation needed|date= December 2014}}\n\n==Education==\nDavis  received a [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] and an MA from the [[University of Pittsburgh]] in 1967,<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> where she held National Science Foundation fellowships as an honors undergraduate and graduate student. A former Scholar in Residence at the [[National Academy of Sciences]], she completed her [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in science studies at the [[University of Chicago]] as a Danforth Fellow, and a [[Master of Public Health|MPH]] at [[Johns Hopkins University]] as a National Cancer Institute post-doctoral fellow.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> She held post-doctoral positions with the [[National Science Foundation]]; in the history, sociology, and philosophy of science at [[Catholic University]] in 1971; and with the World Man Fund and Lorenz K Y Ng, MD at the [[National Institutes of Health]] between 1975 and 1976.\n\n==Professional life==\nFrom 1970 to 1976, Davis was assistant professor of sociology at [[Queens College]] of City University of New York. Between 1982 and 2002, she was a faculty associate at [[Johns Hopkins University]], Department of Health Policy and Management, School of Hygiene and Public Health.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> She has held a number of posts at universities around the world, and {{As of|2011|lc=y}} was Senior Distinguished Visiting Research Scholar in the [[WHO Collaborating Centres|WHO Collaborating Center for Capacity Building in Public Health]] at Hebrew University, Hadassah School of Public Health and Community Medicine.\n\nOther previous positions are as follows:\n* 1985 Visiting Professor, Environmental Medicine, University of Madrid\n* 1989 Visiting Scholar, Unit of Occupational and Environmental Medicine, School of Public Health, [[Hebrew University]]\n* 1994\u20131999 Senior Scientist, [[Strang Cornell Cancer Prevention Center]], New York City\n* 1996-97 Gotteman Distinguished Professor, [[Stern College for Women]] of [[Yeshiva University]], New York City\n* 2000\u20132004 Visiting Professor, H. John Heinz III School of Public Policy and Management, [[Carnegie Mellon University]], Pittsburgh\n* 2000\u20132004 Honorary Professor, [[London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine]], London, England\n* 2001 Visiting Professor, [[Oberlin College]], Department of Environmental Studies, Oberlin, Ohio\n* 2004\u201310 Professor, Department of Epidemiology, Graduate School of Public Health, [[University of Pittsburgh]]\n\nShe served as a visiting scholar at Hebrew University, School of Public Health, Unit of Occupational and Environmental Medicine in 1989.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/>\n\nShe was the founding director of the Center for Environmental Oncology at the [[University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute]]<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> from 2004 to 2010. The multidisciplinary center included experts in medicine, basic research, engineering, and public policy, who developed cutting-edge studies to identify the causes of cancer and propose policies to reduce the risks of the disease. She was also founding director of the National Academies of Sciences, Board on Environmental Studies and Toxicology of the US National Research Council, from 1983 to 1993, and served as Scholar in Residence from 1990 to 1993.\n\n==Other professional activities==\nA member of both the American Colleges of Toxicology and of Epidemiology,<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> Davis was also a visiting professor in the Department of Environmental and Occupational Medicine at [[Mount Sinai Hospital (Manhattan)|Mt. Sinai Medical Center in New York City]],<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> appointed by [[Irving Selikoff]], a founder of occupational medicine in 1988, until that appointment was terminated by [[Philip Landrigan]] in 2010. In addition, she was a visiting scientist of the Strang Cornell Cancer Prevention Center of [[Rockefeller University]] in 1994.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> She also advised the [[World Health Organization]] in developing its program on environmental health indicators and children's environmental health, and traveled with the [[United Nations Development Program]] to China to advise on programmatic issues.\n\nShe served as a member of the Board of Scientific Counselors of the US National Toxicology Program between 1983 and 1986<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> and was a member of the Presidio Advisory Committee to the US government, and a steering committee member of the Department of Defense Breast Cancer Research Program.\n\nIn 2001, Davis became one of the founders of the [[Green Zionist Alliance|Green Zionist Alliance: The Grassroots Campaign for a Sustainable Israel]]<ref name=\"Green Zionist Alliance\">{{cite news | url=http://www.greenzionism.org/about-us/staff-and-board | title=GZA Co-Founders | work=Green Zionist Alliance }}</ref> and was part of the Green Zionist Alliance slate for elections for the World Zionist Congress in 2002.<ref name=\"gzaSlate2002\">{{cite news | url=http://www.greenzionism.org/en/congress/slates/slate2002 | title=GZA 2002 charter delegate slate for the 34th World Zionist Congress | work=Green Zionist Alliance }}</ref>\n\n===Health of women===\nDavis was Scientific Advisor to the Women's Environment and Development Organization in 1995.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> Davis was also a founding member of the International Breast Cancer Prevention Collaborative Research Group,<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> an organization dedicated to exploring the avoidable causes of breast cancer. She, with Lloyd Morgan and [[Michael Kundi]], reported on unexplained differences in brain tumors between men and women at the annual meeting of the Bioelectromagnetics Society.\n\n===Environment===\nDavis has served on the Board of the Climate Institute,<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> the Coalition of Organizations on the Environment and Jewish Life,<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/> and the Earthfire Institute; and is a scientific adviser to the UK registered charity MobileWise.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.mobilewise.org/about-us/our-advisers |title= Our advisors|year= 2011|publisher= MobileWise|accessdate= June 9, 2011}}</ref> She also has advised Green America, Environmental Working Group, the Green Guide, and Healthy Child\u2014non-profit organizations that promote environmental health. She occasionally discusses avoidable environmental health hazards on national and local programming with NPR, Fox News, CNN, ABC, PBS, CBC, BBC,<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> Dutch Public Television, and others.<ref name=\"EHT Home\">{{cite web|url= http://ehtrust.org/home/|title= EHT Home|access-date= December 10, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141213014512/http://ehtrust.org/home/|archive-date= December 13, 2014|url-status= dead}}</ref> She also served as a Lead Author of a chapter on mitigation costs in the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change Third Assessment Report {{cite web|url= http://www.ipcc.ch/ipccreports/tar/wg3/index.php?idp=319|title= IPCC TAR Working Group III: Mitigation }}\n\nShe founded the non-profit Environmental Health Trust in 2007,<ref name=\"EHT_About\" /> with [[David Servan-Schreiber]].{{Citation needed|date= December 2014}}\n\n==Controversies==\nTackling publicly sensitive topics from [[tobacco]], to [[asbestos]] to overuse of diagnostic radiation, Davis's findings and methods have been criticized,<ref>{{Cite web|last= Kinney|first= William H|url= http://www.acsu.buffalo.edu/~whkinney/notevenwrong.html|title= Junk Science: More Research is Needed|accessdate= December 10, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141207221232/http://www.acsu.buffalo.edu/~whkinney/notevenwrong.html|archive-date= December 7, 2014|url-status= dead}}</ref> in some cases being called \"junk science\", especially for raising concerns about [[Wireless device radiation and health|cellphone safety]].<ref>{{cite web|last= Trottier|first= Lorne|author-link= Lorne Trottier|title= A ''Disconnect'' between cell phone fears and science|url= http://www.sciencebasedmedicine.org/a-disconnect-between-cell-phone-fears-and-science/|accessdate= December 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last= Park|first= Bob|author-link= Robert L. Park|title= What's New|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120112021909/http://bobpark.physics.umd.edu/WN10/wn121010.html|date= December 10, 2010|accessdate= December 10, 2014}}</ref> \n\nDavis publicly criticized the prominent epidemiologist Sir [[Richard Doll]], noting in her book ''The Secret History of the War on Cancer'' that his work discovering the link between tobacco and lung cancer in 1955 had been influenced by earlier German studies in the 1930s that he had not acknowledged. [[Richard Horton (editor)|Richard Horton]], editor of ''[[The Lancet]]'', reviewed Davis' work favorably in a lengthy analysis in ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'', taking great exception, however, to her critique of Doll.<ref>{{cite web|last= Horton|first= Richard|author-link= Richard Horton (editor)|title= Cancer: Malignant Maneuvers|url= http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2008/mar/06/cancer-malignant-maneuvers/|date= March 6, 2008|accessdate= December 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nDavis was honored by the Betty Ford Comprehensive Cancer Center and the [[American Cancer Society]] with the Breast Cancer Awareness Award, commended by the Director of the National Cancer Institute for Outstanding Service, and appointed a Global Environmental advisor to ''Newsweek Magazine''.<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/>\n\nShe was a recipient of a Women's Leadership Exchange Compass Award, presented by OPEN: The Small Business Network from [[American Express]], for breaking the paradigms of how women are perceived, Davis received the first Lisa Zhang Environmental Award from the United Nations in July 2008.<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/>\n\nIn June 2009, Davis received the Artemis Award presented by the Euro-American Women's Council and the Greek Foreign Ministry in recognition of her outstanding contributions to science and public health policy.<ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> In 2010, she was awarded the Carnegie Science Medal.  In 2012, she received the Lifetime Achievement Award from [[Green America]].<ref name=\"Huffington Post\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenbusinessnetwork.org/news/business-network-news/item/604-campaign-for-safe-cosmetics-devra-davis-win-green-america%E2%80%99s-bea-awards.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923002704/http://www.greenbusinessnetwork.org/news/business-network-news/item/604-campaign-for-safe-cosmetics-devra-davis-win-green-america%E2%80%99s-bea-awards.html|title=Campaign for Safe Cosmetics, Devra Davis Win Green America\u2019s BEA Awards|date=July 17, 2012|archive-date=September 23, 2012|access-date=February 15, 2017|publisher=[[Green America]]|quote=Dr. Devra Davis also received a Lifetime Achievement for her groundbreaking work on the link between cell phone radiation and brain cancer.|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nShe was also awarded the Nautilus Books Silver Medal for Courageous Reporting,<ref name=\"Huffington Post\"/>and chosen by Amazon editors as a top pick of 2014.\n\n==Publications==\nDavis' books have been translated into Chinese, Turkish, Finnish, Korean, Japanese, and Estonian. She was [[National Book Award]] finalist, for ''When Smoke Ran Like Water'' (2002), which begins with the tale of the [[Donora Smog of 1948]].<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/><ref name=\"EHT_About\"/> \n\nPublications include the following:\n*''Trends in Cancer Mortality in Industrial Countries (Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences)'' (New York Academy of Sciences, 1990). {{ISBN|978-0897666435}}.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/>\n*''Urban Air Pollution Risks to Children: A Global Environmental Health Indicator'' (World Resources Institute, 1999). {{ISBN|978-1569734278}}.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/>\n*''When Smoke Ran Like Water: Tales of Environmental Deception And the Battle Against Pollution''. (Diane Publishing Company, 2002). {{ISBN|978-0465015221}}.\n*''The Secret History of the War on Cancer'' (Basic Books, 2007). {{ISBN|978-0465015689}}.<ref name=\"EHT_CV\"/>\n*''Disconnect: The Truth About Cell Phone Radiation, What the Industry Has Done to Hide It, and How to Protect Your Family'' (Dutton Adult, 2010; paperback, Plume, 2011; Environmental Health Trust, 2013). {{ISBN|978-0991219902}}. Davis also co-produced a 2014 documentary film, ''Mobilize'', based on the book.<ref>{{cite news|last= Moore|first= Chris|title= Are Cell Phones Really Giving Us Cancer?|url= http://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2014/09/15/are-cell-phones-really-giving-us-cancer/|publisher= CBS Pittsburgh|date= 2014-09-15|access-date= 2017-10-08}}</ref>\n\n==Audio recordings==\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=14986010 ''Fresh Air'' interview], October 4, 2007\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080325111838/http://www.writersvoice.net/2008/01/podcast-57-how-everyday-products-make-us-sick/ ''Writer's Voice'' interview], January 2008\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081023214734/http://www.tvo.org/TVO/WebObjects/TVO.woa?video%3FAG_Full_20081003_907694_DevraDavis ''TVO (Ontario)'' interview], October 3, 2008. Length: 26:54\n* Alan Gregg Canada http://allangregg.tvo.org/episode/129397/devra-davis, October 3, 2008\n\n==Mainstream media references==\n* {{cite news|url= http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,2027523,00.html |last= Scherer|first= Michael|title= Cell-Phone Safety: What the FCC Didn't Test|publisher= [[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date= October 26, 2010|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}\n* {{cite web|url= http://magazine.uchicago.edu/1010/features/c-vitae.shtml |first= Ruth E|last= Kott|title= Roaming crusader|work= C. vitae |date=September\u2013October 2010|publisher= University of Chicago Magazine|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Contemporary Authors]] Online. The Gale Group, 2004. PEN (Permanent Entry Number):  0000154775.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.epidemiology.pitt.edu/davis.asp Faculty Bio - Devra Davis] at the Department of Epidemiology, Graduate School of Public Health, University of Pittsburgh\n* [http://www.environmentalhealthtrust.org/ Environmental Health Trust]\n* {{C-SPAN|Devra Davis}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Devra}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:American epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health alumni]]\n[[Category:Women epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:People from Donora, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Taylor Allderdice High School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Qui1che", "label": "safe", "comment": "In Infobox - added hlist template to education parameter and added MPH; removed residence parameter no longer supported by template; added Personal Life section and text with reference to current EHT About web page; updated External link to the latter page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Devra_Davis"}
{"title_page": "Janata Dal (Secular)", "text_new": "{{short description|Political party in India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox Indian Political Party \n|party_name        = Janata Dal (Secular)\n|party_logo        = [[File:JDS-party-symbol.jpg|200px]]\n|colorcode         = {{Janata Dal (Secular)/meta/color}}\n|abbreviation      = JD(S)\n|president         = [[H. D. Deve Gowda]]\n|founder           = [[H. D. Deve Gowda]]\n|loksabha_leader   = [[Prajwal Revanna]]\n|rajyasabha_leader = [[D. Kupendra Reddy]]\n|predecessor       = [[Janata Dal]]\n|foundation        = July 1999\n|alliance          = '''[[United Progressive Alliance|UPA(Karnataka)]]'''\n(2018 - Present)\n'''[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|LDF(Kerala)]]'''\n|colours           = [[Green (color)|Green]] {{Colorsample|Green}}\n|eci               = [[List of political parties in India#State (regional)|State Party]]<ref>{{cite web|title=List of Political Parties and Election Symbols main Notification Dated 18.01.2013|url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/ElectoralLaws/OrdersNotifications/ElecSym19012013_eng.pdf|publisher=Election Commission of India|accessdate=9 May 2013|location=India|year=2013}}</ref>\n|position          =  \n|loksabha_seats    = {{Composition bar|1|543|hex=#138808}}\n|rajyasabha_seats  = {{Composition bar|1|245|hex=#138808}}\n|state_seats_name  = [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]]\n|state_seats       = {{Composition bar|34|224|hex=#138808}}\n|state2_seats_name = [[Kerala Legislative Assembly]]\n|state2_seats      = {{Composition bar|3|140|hex=#138808}}\n|headquarters      = JP Bhavan, 19/1, Platform Road, [[Seshadripuram]], [[Bengaluru]], [[Karnataka]]-560020\n|students          = Student Janata Dal\n|youth             = [[Yuva Janata Dal]]\n|women             = Mahila Janata Dal\n|labour            = Karmikara Janata Dal\n|peasants          = \n|no_states         = {{Composition bar|1|31|hex=#138808}}\n|national_convener = [[H. D. Deve Gowda]]\n|symbol            = [[File:Indian Election Symbol Lady Farmer.png|Janata Dal Election Symbol|150px]]\n|website           = {{url|http://jds.ind.in/}} \n|ideology         = [[Secularism]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jds.ind.in/ideology/ |title=Official website ideology section |publisher=Jds.ind.in |date=2014-10-26 |accessdate=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Janata Dal (Secular)''' is an [[India]]n political party<ref>{{cite web|url=http://janatadals.com/aboutparty.php|title=History of Janata Dal (Secular) according to its website|accessdate=2007-09-30}}</ref> led by former [[List of Prime Ministers of India|Prime Minister of India]], [[H. D. Deve Gowda]]. The party is recognized as a [[List of political parties in India#State (regional)|State Party]] in the states of [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Arunachal Pradesh]]. It was formed in July 1999 by the split of [[Janata Dal]] party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19991113/ipo13028.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201104233/http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19991113/ipo13028.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 February 2009|title=EC to hear Janata Dal symbol dispute|accessdate=2007-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.india-today.com/itoday/19990802/jd.html|title=The Nation:Janata Dal:Divided Gains (India Today article)|accessdate=2007-09-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109210028/http://www.india-today.com/itoday/19990802/jd.html|archive-date=9 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> It has a political presence mainly in Karnataka. In Kerala, the party is a part of the [[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|Left Democratic Front]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:JD-S-propaganda-Kannada-Bangalore.jpg|thumb|JD(S) promotion art-work in [[Bangalore]].]]\nThe Janata Dal(Secular),formed in 1999, had its origins in the [[Janata Party]],founded in 1977 as a coalition of several smaller parties that combined forces to oppose the [[Indian National Congress]].<ref name=\"britannica.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.britannica.com/topic/Janata-Dal-Secular|title=britannica.com : Janata Dal (Secular)}}</ref> In 1988 the Janata Party and other smaller parties merged to form the [[Janata Dal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lokpriya.com/personalities/political/present/chandrashekhar.html|title=article on Chandrashekar|accessdate=2007-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindujobs.com/thehindu/mp/2006/01/17/stories/2006011700490300.html|title=Bouquet of ideologies - article in the Hindu|accessdate=2007-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tiscali.co.uk/reference/encyclopaedia/hutchinson/m0029548.html|title=Janata Dal|accessdate=2007-09-30}}</ref> In 1996, Janata Dal reached its pinnacle when [[H. D. Deve Gowda]] became Prime Minister of India, heading the [[United Front (India)|United Front]] (UF) coalition government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pmindia.nic.in/pm_gowda.htm|title=Profile of Deve Gowda on PMO website|accessdate=2007-09-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010020723/http://pmindia.nic.in/pm_gowda.htm|archivedate=10 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[http://jds.ind.in/histor/ History \u00ab Welcome to Janata Dal (Secular) Official Website]. Jds.ind.in. Retrieved on 2014-05-21.</ref>\n\nThe [[Janata Dal]] split in 1999, when a faction led by Chief Minister [[J. H. Patel]] lent support to the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]-led [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|National Democratic Alliance]] leading to the formation of Janata Dal(Secular) under [[H. D. Deve Gowda]] and [[Siddaramaiah]]. The [[Sharad Yadav]] faction of the Janata Dal, the Lok Shakti and the Samata Party merged as the [[Janata Dal (United)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janata.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=53&Itemid=60|title=Janata.in|website=www.janata.in}}</ref><ref>[http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2108/stories/20040423006701900.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103051657/http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl2108/stories/20040423006701900.htm |date=3 January 2008 }}</ref> Even though the premise for the split was its opposition to allying with the [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|National Democratic Alliance]], [[H. D. Deve Gowda]] stayed equally away from the [[Indian National Congress]] from the outset.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/1999/99aug26/head2.htm|title=\"Gowda rules out tieup with Congress \" - Tribune India article|accessdate=2007-09-30}}</ref>\n\nJD(S) in Karnataka state for a time governed in a coalition with the incic inc\n [[Indian National Congress]] (INC) party, the first coalition government in Karnataka. There was much controversy over the JD(S) allying with the INC in [[Bangalore]] as the INC formerly had an outright majority and was diminished to second place with the BJP having a plurality. However, the JD(S) considered INC to be the lesser of the two evils on account of its erstwhile secular and center-left credentials.\n\nThe [[2004 Karnataka Legislative Assembly election|2004 Karnataka Assembly election]] witnessed the revival of the party's fortunes with JD(S) becoming part of the ruling coalition in the state.\n\nOn 14 April 2015, the JD(S), [[Janata Dal (United)]], [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]], the [[Indian National Lok Dal]], [[Samajwadi Party]], and [[Samajwadi Janata Party (Rashtriya)]] announced that they would merge into a new national Janata Parivar alliance in order to oppose the BJP, thus leaving the UPA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/india/janata-parivar-formalised-mulayam-singh-named-chief-of-new-party_1578871.html |title='Janata Parivar' formalised, Mulayam Singh named chief of new party &#124; Zee News |publisher=Zeenews.india.com |date=2015-04-15 |accessdate=2017-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Prominent Members==\n<!--PLEASE DO NOT MAKE ADDITIONS TO THIS LIST WHICH DO NOT HAVE APPROPRIATE REFERENCES-->\n<!--ALSO, ENTRIES SHOULD HAVE ARTICLES-->\n\n* [[H. D. Deve Gowda]], President of Janata Dal (Secular), former [[List of Prime Ministers of India|Prime Minister of India]] and Former [[List of Chief Ministers of Karnataka|Chief Minister of Karnataka]].\n* [[H. D. Kumaraswamy]], former [[List of Chief Ministers of Karnataka|Chief Minister of Karnataka]], son of former Prime Minister of India [[H. D. Deve Gowda]] and Former Karnataka State President of Janata Dal (Secular).\n* [[Nikhil Gowda]], State President, Yuva Janata Dal (Secular).\n* [[Prajwal Revanna]], [[Member of parliament|MP]] of [[Hassan (Lok Sabha constituency)|Hassan]], [[Lok Sabha]] leader of Janata Dal (Secular).\n*[[Basavaraj Horatti]], Former Chairman of [[Vidhana parishad|Karnataka Legislative Council]], and Former Cabinet minister of Karnataka\n* [[B. M. Farooq]], Current MLC of Karnataka Legislative Council, Current National General Secretary Of Janata Dal (Secular).\n*[[C. S. Puttaraju]], Former minister for small irrigation resources, and former [[Member of parliament, Lok Sabha]] from [[Mandya]].\n*[[GT Devegowda]], Former minister for higher education, and [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] from [[Chamundeshwari (Vidhana Sabha constituency)]].\n*\n* [[Sarekoppa Bangarappa]], Former [[List of Chief Ministers of Karnataka|Chief Minister of Karnataka]].<ref>[http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=91750n_tit=Bangarappa+Switches+Parties+Ninth+Time%2C+Joins+JD%28S%29 D A I J I W O R L D]. D A I J I W O R L D (2011-08-10). Retrieved on 2014-05-21.</ref>\n* [[N. M. Joseph]], Vice President of Janata Dal (Secular).\n* [[H. D. Revanna]], former Cabinet Minister, Present MLA, Karnataka (Son of H. D. Deve Gowda).\n*[[D. Kupendra Reddy]], [[Member of parliament|MP]] of [[Rajya Sabha]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/kupendra-reddy-files-papers-as-jds-candidate-for-rs-polls/article6093755.ece|title=Kupendra Reddy files papers as JD(S) candidate for RS polls|date=2014-06-08|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-02-23|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prsindia.org/mptrack/dkupendrareddy|title=D. Kupendra Reddy|date=2016-10-25|website=PRSIndia|language=en|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n*[[Mathew T. Thomas]], former Kerala State President of Janata Dal (Secular) and former Kerala State Minister.\n* [[Madhu Bangarappa]], former MLA of Karnataka Legislative Assembly.\n* [[Jose Thettayil]], Vice President of Janata Dal (Secular), former minister Govt. of Kerala.\n* [[C. K. Nanu]], State President of JD(S) Kerala, former minister Govt. of Kerala and MLA.\n* [[Neelalohithadasan Nadar]], former Kerala State President of Janata Dal (Secular) (former Minister Govt. of Kerala; former Member of Parliament, Govt. of India).\n* [[Mohamed Zafrulla Khan]] National General Secretary, former Chairman KMDC \n* [[K. Krishnankutty]],current Kerala State Minister for Water Resources.\n* [[Gegong Apang]], former [[Chief Minister of Arunachal Pradesh]]\n* Tanveer Ahmed, National Spokesperson, Janata Dal (Secular).\n\n==Chief Ministers==\n* [[H. D. Deve Gowda]] - 11 December 1994 to 31 May 1996\n* [[H. D. Kumaraswamy]] \u2013 3 February 2006 to 9 October 2007, 23 May 2018 to 23 July 2019.\n\n==Assembly election history in Karnataka==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year || Assembly Election || Seats Contested || Seats Won || Votes Secured || Percentage Of Votes\n|-\n| 1999 || 11th Assembly || 203 || 10 || 23,16,885 ||10.42%<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/StatisticalReports/SE_1999/StatisticalReport-KT99.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111111511/http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/StatisticalReports/SE_1999/StatisticalReport-KT99.pdf |archive-date=11 January 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|2004 || 12th Assembly || 220 || 59 || 52,20,121 || 20.77%<ref>[http://eci.nic.in/eci_main/StatisticalReport