ers]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Conservative Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of the Rising Sun]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the Companions of Honour]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rutlish School]]\n[[Category:People from Brixton]]\n[[Category:History of the London Borough of Lambeth]]\n[[Category:People from Carshalton]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Chatham House]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Surrey County Cricket Club]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the European Council]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n", "name_user": "WisDom-UK", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly Parliamentary career (1979\u20131987)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Major"}
{"title_page": "Empire Corridor", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| box_width        = \n| name             = Empire Corridor\n| other_name       = \n| color            = \n| logo             =  \n| logo_width       = \n| logo_alt         = \n| image            = corridor ne.PNG\n| image_width      = 300px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = Empire Corridor (red) as designated by the [[Federal Railroad Administration]]\n| type             = [[Higher-speed rail]], [[commuter rail]]\n| system           = [[Amtrak]]<br>[[CSX Transportation]]\n| status           = \n| locale           = \n| start            = [[Niagara Falls station (New York)|Niagara Falls]]\n| end              = [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|New York Penn Station]]\n| stations         = 35 (12 Amtrak, 20 Metro North, 3 shared)\n| routes           = [[Empire Service]], [[Ethan Allen Express]], [[Adirondack (train)|Adirondack]], [[Lake Shore Limited]], [[Maple Leaf (train)|Maple Leaf]], [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]]\n| daily_ridership  = \n| ridership2       = \n| planopen         = <!--{{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}-->\n| open             = <!--{{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}-->\n| yearcommenced    = <!--{{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}-->\n| yearcompleted    = <!--{{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}-->\n| close            = <!--{{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}}-->\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[CSX Transportation|CSX]] (Niagara\u2013Poughkeepsie)<br>[[Metro-North Railroad|Metro-North]] (Poughkeepsie\u2013Riverdale)<br>[[Amtrak]] (Riverdale\u2013New York)\n| operator         = CSX (Niagara\u2013Schenectady)<br>Amtrak (Schenectady\u2013Poughkeepsie)<br>Metro-North (Poughkeepsie\u2013Yonkers)<br>Amtrak (Yonkers\u2013New York)\n| character        = \n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength_mi    = 461\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = \n| speed_mph        = \n| signalling       =\n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = \n| map_name         = \n| map_state        = uncollapsed\n| embedded         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Empire Corridor''' is a term used to refer to the {{convert|461|mi|km|adj=on}} railroad corridor between [[Niagara Falls, New York]] and [[New York City]], including the cities of [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[Syracuse, New York|Syracuse]], [[Utica, New York|Utica]], [[Amsterdam, New York|Amsterdam]], [[Schenectady, New York|Schenectady]], [[Albany, New York|Albany]], and [[Poughkeepsie, New York| Poughkeepsie]]. Amtrak's ''[[Empire Service]]'' and ''[[Maple Leaf (train)|Maple Leaf]]'' serve the entire length of the corridor, with the ''Maple Leaf'' continuing to [[Toronto]]. ''[[Lake Shore Limited]]'' trains from [[Chicago Union Station|Chicago]] join the Empire Corridor just before {{amtk|Buffalo\u2013Depew}} station, and continue to Albany, where half of each train diverges to Boston, and the other half continues to New York City. The ''[[Ethan Allen Express]]'' and ''[[Adirondack (train)|Adirondack]]'' follow the corridor between New York and {{amtk|Schenectady}}, after which they diverge and continue on to {{amtk|Rutland}} and {{amtk|Montreal}}, respectively. [[Metro-North Railroad]]'s [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]] provides commuter rail service between [[Poughkeepsie, New York]] and [[Grand Central Terminal]]. The line is electrified by both [[Overhead line|overhead catenary]] and top-running [[third rail]] on the Amtrak-owned segment between [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]] and 41st Street, and by under-running [[third rail]] on the Metro-North segment from [[Grand Central Terminal]] to {{mnrr|Croton\u2013Harmon}}. \n\nThe corridor is also one of ten federally designated [[High-speed rail in the United States|high-speed rail]] corridors in the [[United States]].\n\nIf the proposed high-speed service were built on the corridor, trains traveling between Buffalo and New York City would travel at speeds of up to {{convert|125|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. In the 1890s service on the [[Empire State Express]] service between New York City and Buffalo was about 1 hour faster than Amtrak's service in 2013. On September 14, 1891 the Empire State Express covered the {{convert|436|mi|km}} between New York City and Buffalo in 7&nbsp;hours and 6&nbsp;minutes (including stops), averaging {{convert|61.4|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, with a top speed of {{convert|82|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"KUHF\">{{cite web| url=http://www.kuhf.org/cdprojects/steam/track12.html| title=Rain, Steam & Speed: Inventing Powered Motion| author=John Lienhard| accessdate=January 28, 2007}}</ref><ref name=NYT1893>{{cite news| url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1893/05/12/106864316.pdf| title=GREAT SPEED Off THE CENTRAL.; Empire State Express Engine Travels at the Rate of 112 1-2 Miles an Hour| publisher=New York Times| date=May 12, 1893| format=PDF| accessdate=December 13, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Ownership==\nThe Empire Corridor is largely owned by [[CSX Transportation]] (CSX), which owns the trackage between Niagara Falls and [[Poughkeepsie, New York|Poughkeepsie]].<ref name=\"timetable\">Amtrak system timetable, Fall 2010/Winter 2011, page 25</ref> Amtrak owns trackage rights for most of the Hudson line section north of Poughkeepsie to their rail yard in Albany. South of Poughkeepsie, the Empire Corridor is coextensive with Metro-North's trackage until it forks off between Metro-North's Riverdale and Spuyten Duyvil stations in the Bronx, to cross the [[Harlem River]] over the [[Spuyten Duyvil Bridge]] and make the [[Empire Connection]] to Penn Station. Amtrak owns the trackage after that fork, the [[West Side Line]].\n\nThe corridor had been part of the main line of the [[New York Central Railroad]]; it was the eastern leg of the NYC's famed \"Water Level Route\" to [[Chicago]]. The corridor passed to [[Penn Central Transportation Company|Penn Central]] in 1968 upon the NYC's merger with the [[Pennsylvania Railroad]], and passed to [[Conrail]] in 1976. In a series of purchases in the 1980s and 1990s, Amtrak bought the Bronx-Manhattan segment, Metro-North acquired the Poughkeepsie-Bronx segment, and CSX acquired the remainder when it split Conrail's assets with [[Norfolk Southern Railway|Norfolk Southern]].\n\nOn October 18, 2011, Amtrak and CSX announced an agreement for Amtrak to lease, operate and maintain the CSX-owned trackage between Poughkeepsie and Schenectady.<ref name=\"lease\">{{cite web|title=Amtrak to lease Empire Corridor trackage from CSX|url=http://trn.trains.com/en/Railroad%20News/News%20Wire/2011/10/Amtrak%20to%20lease%20Empire%20Corridor%20trackage%20from%20CSX.aspx|publisher=Trains Magazine|accessdate=October 19, 2011|date=October 18, 2011}}</ref> Amtrak officially assumed control of the line on December 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Governor Cuomo Announces Hudson Rail Lease - Amtrak/CSX Deal Will Improve Passenger Service, Move Projects Forward|date=December 4, 2012|publisher=[[Amtrak]]|location=[[Albany, New York]]|url=http://www.amtrak.com/ccurl/13/26/Amtrak-CSX-Hudson-Line-Release-ATK-12-126.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Current services==\nThe busiest segment of the Empire Corridor is between New York City and [[Albany, New York|Albany]] with multiple trains per day.\n\n===Amtrak===\nThe following trains operate along the varied segments of the corridor:\n*''[[Empire Service]]'': local service along the entire corridor from [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|New York City]] to {{amtk|Niagara Falls, NY}}. Most trains operate along the southern segment between New York and {{amtk|Albany}}, with two trains in each direction continuing west to Niagara Falls daily.\n*''[[Ethan Allen Express]]'': one train in each direction daily from New York City to {{amtk|Rutland}}, splitting from the corridor in Schenectady.\n*''[[Adirondack (train)|Adirondack]]'': New York City to {{amtk|Montreal}}, splitting from the corridor in Schenectady.\n*''[[Lake Shore Limited]]'': New York City to {{amtk|Chicago}}, splitting from the corridor at {{amtk|Buffalo\u2013Depew}}, though a section of the train splits off in Albany to serve [[South Station|Boston]] instead of New York.\n*''[[Maple Leaf (train)|Maple Leaf]]'': daily service from New York City to {{amtk|Toronto}}, operating on the entire corridor.\n\n===Commuter rail===\n*[[Metro-North Railroad|Metro-North Railroad's]] [[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|Hudson Line]], from [[Poughkeepsie, New York]] to [[Grand Central Terminal]], New York\n\n===Freight service===\nFreight service is provided by [[CSX Transportation]].\n\n==Stations==\nAll stations are in the [[New York (state)|state of New York]].\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Location\n!rowspan=2 nowrap=yes|[[Railway milepost|Mile (km)]]\n!rowspan=2|Station\n!rowspan=2|Current station opened\n!colspan=6 class=unsortable|Corridor services\n!rowspan=2 class=unsortable|Connections\n|-\n!class=unsortable|[[Empire Service|ES]]\n!class=unsortable|[[Maple Leaf (train)|ML]]\n!class=unsortable|[[Lake Shore Limited|LS]]\n!class=unsortable|[[Adirondack (train)|AD]]\n!class=unsortable|[[Ethan Allen Express|EA]]\n!class=unsortable|[[Hudson Line (Metro-North)|HD]]\n|-\n|[[Niagara Falls, New York|Niagara Falls]]\n|{{convert|461|mi|km|abbr=values}}\n|[[Niagara Falls station (New York)|Niagara Falls]]\n|December 6, 2016<ref name=greatstations>{{cite web |url=https://www.greatamericanstations.com/stations/ |title=Building Great American Stations |publisher=[[Amtrak]] |accessdate=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|\u25cf || \u25cf || || || ||\n|\n|-